<html>
<title>THE STRAIGHT STORY ON NEW JERSEY</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/insight/insight.gif">
<p>
<h2>THE STRAIGHT STORY<br>
ON NEW JERSEY:<br>
BIRTHS, ABORTIONS, AND THE FAMILY CAP</h2>
<hr size = 3 width = 50%>
<p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Michael Schwartz</i><br>
<i>Life Advocacy Alliance</i></center>
<p>
In August of 1993, the first &quot;family cap&quot; in the nation
took effect in the state of New Jersey as part of a larger package
of reforms known as the Family Development Program.  The family
cap provision stipulates that a mother who has already received
welfare benefits for at least 10 months and who bears an additional
child will receive no increase in her basic monthly AFDC benefit.
 The provision affects only the monthly <I>cash</I> benefit, however.
 Health benefits and food stamps continue to increase with family
size.
<P>
The raw numbers of births and abortions in New Jersey since the
cap took effect strongly suggest that the policy has reduced the
number of births to AFDC mothers without affecting the abortion
rate.
<P>
Raw data for the 20-month period from August 1992 to March 1994
appears in Table 1:
<P><hr><p>
<center><h3>TABLE 1</h3></center>
<PRE WIDTH=132>
<B>MONTH</B>           CASELOAD      ABORTIONS      BIRTHS       TOTAL        

<B>August 1992</B>     118,122       902            1366         2268         

<B>September 1992</B>  118,739       935            1317         2252         

<B>October 1992</B>    119,386       1022           1351         2373         

<B>November 1992</B>   120,957       814            1299         2113         

<B>December 1992</B>   121,626       869            1396         2265         

<B>January 1993</B>    121,928       1023           1439         2462         

<B>February 1993</B>   122,270       943            1197         2140         

<B>March 1993</B>      122,734       1111           1338         2449         

<B>April 1993</B>      123,197       1110           1219         2329         

<B>May 1993</B>        123,300       944            1248         2192         

<B>June 1993</B>       122,677       1101           1352         2453         

<B>July 1993</B>       122,810       1043           1450         2493         

<B>August 1993</B>     122,610       1050           1267         2317         

<B>September 1993</B>  122,817       883            1231         2114         

<B>October 1993</B>    122,426       933            1164         2097         

<B>November 1993</B>   122,581       942            1110         2052         

<B>December 1993</B>   122,746       979            1208         2187         

<B>January 1994</B>    122,718       924            1223         2147         

<B>February 1994</B>   122,590       960            1090         2050         

<B>March 1994</B>      122,940       1261           1226         2487         
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>
The total number of abortions in the year before the policy took
effect was 11,817, yielding a monthly average of 984.75.  In the
eight months after the policy took effect (including March 1994,
which had a far higher total of abortions than any other month
on record), the total number of abortions was 7,932, yielding
a monthly average of 991.5.  The difference (0.7%) is trivial
and well within the expected range of random fluctuation.  If
the anomalous month of March were excluded from the analysis,
the average would be just 953 abortions per month after the introduction
of the family cap -- a 3% decline from the previous year's average,
but also trivial enough to be within the range of random fluctuation.
<P>
A more comprehensive look at the data reduces the significance
of the difference even further.  The average monthly caseload
in the year before the family cap was enacted was 121,479.  In
the eight months post-cap, the average monthly caseload was 122,679
-- a difference of less than 1%.  But the monthly abortion rate
(number of abortions per 1,000 AFDC cases) was 8.11 in the year
prior to enactment of the family cap and only 8.08 in the eight
months post-enactment.  The difference is too small to be statistically
significant, but it is worth noting that the total number of abortions
in the period after implementation of the cap was three <I>fewer</I>
than predicted by the rate before enactment of the policy.
<P>
Using the entire preceding year as the baseline, however, tends
to distort the real effect of the family cap because the abortion
rate was very low in the period ranging from August to November
1992.  During the eight months immediately preceding the introduction
of the cap (December 1992 to July 1993), New Jersey welfare mothers
underwent 8,144 abortions -- 212 <I>more</I> than in the eight
months after the cap took effect.  If the post-cap data did not
include the month of March 1994, moreover, the post-cap abortion
average would have been 8% less than the average for the previous
seven months.
<P>
No responsible statistician would therefore conclude that the
family cap must reduce abortions.  But an honest evaluation of
the available data strongly argues that, contrary to the fears
expressed by many in the pro-life community, the family cap has
had no impact on the number or rate of abortions among New Jersey's
AFDC recipients.  The monthly abortion totals fluctuated with
no apparent pattern, but were always within the expected range.
 The total number of abortions in the eight months post-cap was
almost exactly what would have been projected if there had been
no change in the state's welfare policy.
<P>
The birth rate among AFDC recipients, on the other hand, was significantly
lower after introduction of the family cap.  In the year prior
to the cap, the total number of births to welfare mothers in New
Jersey was 15,972, yielding a monthly average of 1,331 births
and a monthly rate of 10.96 births per thousand AFDC recipients.
 In the eight months post-cap, there were 9,519 births, yielding
a monthly average of 1,190 births and a monthly rate of 9.70 births
per thousand AFDC recipients.  The difference is consistent, substantial,
and statistically significant.
<P>
In all eight months after the introduction of the cap, the birth
totals were below the previous year's average and lower than the
total for the corresponding month in the previous year.  The monthly
abortion totals after implementation of the cap show a more random
pattern.  In six of the eight months, there were fewer abortions
than the previous year's average, but in only three of those months
was the abortion total lower than the total for the corresponding
month the year before.
<P>
When the entire 20-month period is divided into 4-month increments
(see Table 2), the change in the average number of births is obvious.
 The family cap has produced a significant reduction in the number
of births and pregnancies, but has had no discernible impact on
the number of abortions.
<P><hr><p>
<center><h3>TABLE 2</h3></center>
<PRE WIDTH=132>
<B>Date</B>                        Caseload        Births     Abortions     Total     

<B>August-November 1992</B>        119,299         5333       3673          9006      

<B>December 1992-March 1993</B>    122,140         5370       3946          9316      

<B>April-July 1993</B>             122,996         5269       4198          9467      

<B>August-November 1993</B>        122,609         4772       3808          8580      

<B>December 1993-March 1994</B>    122,707         4747       4124          8871      

</PRE>
<HR>
<P>
<P>
The only way to calculate a higher abortion rate for the post-cap
period is to suppress the data from April to July 1993 -- the
period immediately prior to implementation of the new policy --
and compare the abortion totals from the post-cap period with
the totals from the corresponding months of the previous year.
 <I>Unless the April to July 1993 data is suppressed, </I>the
abortion rate after implementation of the family cap appears to
be either the same as or lower than the abortion rate before the
cap.
<P>
There are only two hypotheses that could justify suppressing the
April to July 1993 data and preserve the finding that the abortion
rate has increased since implementation of the cap.
<P>
First, it is possible that the abortion rate follows an annual
cyclical pattern and that the monthly abortion totals from April
to July 1994 will show the same inflation as in 1993.  But a close
examination of the month-by-month totals suggests that the high
months and low months in the two years do not correspond with
enough consistency to indicate a seasonal cycle.  In 1992-1993,
the months with high abortion totals were October, January, and
March, while August, November, and December registered low totals.
 In 1993-1994, August and March were the months with a high number
of abortions, and the September total was relatively low.
<P>
The second hypothesis is that welfare mothers may have staged
an &quot;abortion rush&quot; prior to implementation of the family
cap, thereby generating unusually high abortion totals in the
months immediately preceding the change in policy.  But the single
month in which an &quot;abortion rush&quot; would have been most
visible, July 1993, had a lower abortion total than either June
1993 or August 1993.  The number of abortions declined between
June and July and increased between July and August.  The time
period with the highest number of abortions spanned six months,
from March to August -- straddling the enactment date -- and then
was followed by six months of low abortion totals after implementation
of the family cap.
<P>
While it is still premature to draw any decisive conclusions from
the welfare reform experiment in New Jersey, it is becoming increasingly
fantastic to claim that the state has experienced an upsurge in
abortions since the family cap took effect.  The reported &quot;increase&quot;
in abortions rests on a statistical illusion created by suppressing
data from the four-month period immediately preceding the policy
change -- which includes the highest abortion totals recorded
in the data under study.
<P>
Those who would hold welfare reform hostage in the name of saving
lives bear a significant burden of proof in maintaining that more
lives will be saved by preserving the current welfare system.
 The consistent, strong correlation between increased welfare
spending and increased abortions should be far more troublesome
data to pro-lifers than the most recent numbers from New Jersey.
<P>
-- 8/31/95
<P>
<center>***</center>
<P>
<I>Michael Schwartz is the director of Life Advocacy Alliance.</I>

<p>

<center>
<b>
