reviewed the research on Head Start in 1990 and found that &quot;results
from Head Start projects are uncertain for the special education
effects, and there is virtually no evidence [that Head Start reduces]
teen pregnancy, crime, welfare, or unemployment.&quot; (From a
telephone interview with the author on March 8, 1995.)
<p>
<li>Cited in CPB's FCC brief, the study was conducted by Westat,
Inc. for CPB, based on data from the National Household Educational
Survey of 1993 conducted by the U.S. Department of Education.
<p>
<li>Summarized in Kay S. Hymowitz, &quot;On  Sesame Street, It's
All Show,&quot; <I>City Journal</I>, The Manhattan Institute,
New York, Autumn, 1995, 60-69.
<p>
<li><I>Ibid,</I> at 62.
<p>
<li>The Corporation for Public Broadcasting is committed to send a
&quot;minimum of $5 million &quot; to the Public Broadcasting
Service for fiscal year 1997 to be &quot;used exclusively for
children's programming.&quot;  Source: CPB's FCC comments.
<p>
<li>A study commissioned by the National Association of Broadcasters
found that the average commercial station aired 3.6 hours of 
children's  educational programming a week in 1993, compared with
only 2 hours per week in 1990.  In its FCC brief, CBS News also
cited an INTV study that found &quot;the average independent station
aired 4.64 hours per week in the first quarter of 1994.&quot;
 The brief notes that pro-intervention academic Dr. Dale Kunkel
of University of California at Santa Barbara found an average
of 3.4 hours per week in a study based on license renewal applications
filed in 1992.  Kunkel has challenged the validity of some of
the claims, however.
<p>
<li>Remarks by Sen. Daniel Inouye, 136 <I>Congressional Record S
10122 (daily ed. July 19, 1990.) </I>
<p>
<li>Comments of the Corporation for Public Broadcasting before the
FCC, MM Docket No. 93-48, at 2. 
<p>
<li><I>Ibid, </I>at 3.
<p>
<li><I>Ibid</I>, citing remarks of Sen. Inouye on July 19.
