<html>
<title>Wrong Way to Honor Reagan -- Heritage Commentary</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>

<h3><i>Wrong Way To Honor Reagan</i></h3>
By <a href="/heritage/staff/feulner.html">Edwin Feulner</a><br>
President, <a href="/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a><br>
January 26, 1995<br>
<hr width=50%></center><p>
	What's the best way to pay tribute to a former president?  
<p>
	Well, some have had their faces chiseled into the sides of a famous mountain. A few have 
earned -- pardon the pun -- a stamp of approval, with their likeness adorning stamps issued by the 
U.S. Postal Service. Others appear on our dollar bills and coins. And some even get buildings 
named after them. Usually this makes a good deal of sense. Usually -- but not always. 
<P>
	Consider what's happening in Washington. A soon-to-be-famous building -- or maybe I 
should say, infamous -- now called the Federal Triangle Project needs a name.  
<p>
 	Located two blocks from the White House, this half-a-billion dollar government colossus is 
millions and millions of dollars over budget, lavish beyond compare, and almost four years behind 
schedule.  
<p>
	The building has 3.1 million square feet of space -- second in size only to the huge 
Pentagon complex, which has 3.9 million square feet. It sprawls across 11 acres and rises 10 stories 
high, with five more levels underground. When the complex opens in December 1996, it will have 
85 elevators, eight escalators, a six-story atrium, 13,000 doors, limestone exteriors, a limestone 
rotunda, 904 windows, several live-performance theaters, a health club, an elaborate food court, 
storefront offices, and plans for a 620-seat auditorium and movie theater. Now the bureaucrats can 
enjoy a movie during their extended coffee breaks! 
<p>
	As the most grandiose government building ever erected, the Federal Triangle Project 
represents the ultimate monument to government waste. 
<p>
	So whose name do you think they want to put on this monstrosity? Lyndon Johnson, who 
launched the government's failed $5.4 trillion War on Poverty? Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., 
maybe? He's long been known as Mr. Pork Barrel on Capitol Hill.  
<p>
	Nope. Actually official Washington has proposed naming the building after the man who 
tried hardest to stop wasteful government spending, the anti-waste crusader himself: Ronald 
Reagan. 
<p>
	Incredible, but true. Senate Majority Leader Robert Dole, R-Kan. and Sen. Daniel P.  
Moynihan, D-N.Y., want to honor the former president by naming the structure the Ronald 
Reagan Building and International Trade Center. 
<p>
	They ought to know better. Reagan is the one president in recent memory most identified 
with fighting big government. In his eight years in the White House, he waged a relentless battle to 
bring big government to heel. Now they want to honor this valiant effort with a building costing 
$656 million: the most expensive government building ever.
<p>
	Someone needs to stop this travesty. Ronald Reagan wanted to reduce the size of 
government, not expand it. He wanted to get the bureaucracy off the backs of the American people, 
not house it in palatial splendor. Naming this bureaucratic Taj Mahal in his honor seems the least 
fitting tribute I can think of.
<p>
	Ironically, some of the agencies hand-picked by Clinton administration officials to move 
into the complex would have been eliminated during the Reagan era if Congress would have gone 
along.
<p>
	There are lots of  better ways to honor President Reagan than by putting his name on this 
government monstrosity. As his son, radio talk-show host Michael Reagan, said recently, Ronald 
Reagan should be on Mount Rushmore. Not Mount Wastemore.  
<p>

Note: <a href="/heritage/staff/feulner.html">Edwin Feulner</a> is president of <a href="/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a>, a Washington-based public policy research institute. 


<p><p><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP 
BORDER=0></A></CENTER></body>
