<html>

<title>BEIJING'S AFTERMATH: A CLOSER LOOK AT THE U.N. CONFERENCE</title>

<body>

<center>

<img src="/townhall/FRC/fampol/fampolgn.gif">

<h1>Beijing's Aftermath</h1>
<h2><i>A Closer Look at the U.N. Conference</i></h2>

</center>

<font size=+3>A</font>fter much heated debate prior to and during the 
United Nations Fourth World Conference on Women in Beijing, China, the 
final Platform for Action was adopted on September 15, 1995.

<p>

What does the final document say?  And what are the implications of the
document for families, both in America and abroad?  This report
seeks to answer these questions as well as to shed light on the
inner processes surrounding the adoption of the Beijing Platform.

<p>

<center><h3>General Assessment</h3></center>

<p>

The United Nations spent $2.5 million to sponsor the Beijing
conference -- $1.8 million for conference services and $700,000
for public information.  Moreover, China incurred additional expenses
to host the event.  It took 12 days and a half-dozen committees
for the 4,969 delegates representing 189 countries to hammer out
the Beijing Platform for Action -- all the time under constant
pressure from 4,020 non-governmental organizations (NGOs) and
the watchful eyes of 3,235 members of the media.

<p>

The Beijing document, written over the course of two years, primarily
by NGOs from the old-line radical women's movement in collaboration
with several U.N. staff, arrived in Beijing with one third of
its text in brackets to show it was under challenge by various
government delegates.  (Brackets denoted areas of the text which
were disputed by government delegates.  No brackets could remain
in the final document.)

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
What the feminists wanted<br>
from the Beijing conference<br>
was a redefinition of 'woman'<br>
in the radical feminist mold.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

The document that emerged from Beijing was an unwieldy mixture
of ideas, reflecting, in part, the many different factions represented.
But by far, this &quot;agenda for women's empowerment&quot; was
most heavily influenced by radical feminists advocating a &quot;gender
perspective.&quot;  In fact, several prominent national delegations
were led by radical feminists -- notably those from the United States,
Canada, Australia, New Zealand, the Caribbean and the European
Union.  These delegations demonstrated their determination to
extend international recognition of women's reproductive &quot;rights&quot;
beyond the Cairo Conference of 1994.

<p>

What the feminists wanted from the Beijing conference was a redefinition
of &quot;woman&quot; in the radical feminist mold.  They wanted
the U.N. to declare that women had a universal right to abortion
and that abortion was an acceptable means of family planning.
They wanted to enshrine the &quot;rights&quot; of adolescents
to information and medical services where sex and AIDS were concerned,
without the &quot;interference&quot; of parents.  They wanted
an endorsement of &quot;sexual orientation&quot; as an entree
for lesbian &quot;rights&quot; and, short of that, they wanted
the phrase &quot;in all its various forms&quot; appended to all
mentions of &quot;the family&quot; in the document, so as to make
way for non-traditional unions.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Abortion was not declared<br>
a universal right nor<br>
accepted as a means of<br>
family planning in the<br>
Platform. However, controlling<br>
one's reproductive activity<br>
was declared a 'human right.'
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

What the feminists ended up with was something in between.  Abortion
was not declared a universal right nor accepted as a means of
family planning in the Platform.  However, controlling one's sexual 
and reproductive activity was declared
a &quot;human right.&quot;  Parents' rights were not completely
overruled, but they were subordinated to &quot;the best interests
of the child.&quot; Lesbian &quot;rights&quot; language was finally excluded 
at 4:45 a.m. the day scheduled for the adoption of the document, as weary
delegates looking for a few hours of sleep simply deleted all
references to sexual orientation from the document.  Nonetheless,
as Main Committee Chair Patricia Licuanan pointed out, this did
not change the fact that the day before, for the first time, a
lesbian had addressed a U.N. plenary on behalf of lesbian &quot;rights.&quot;

<p>

<center><h3>Issues in the Beijing Document</h3></center>

<p>

It must be acknowledged that the Beijing document contains some
positive aspects in that it denounces many terrible injustices
still suffered by women -- especially women in the Third World.
For example, the Platform denounces societies where son-preference
is practiced.  It spotlights poverty as a cause of women's suffering.
It condemns domestic battering and harassment in the workplace
and denounces forced prostitution, pornography, female genital
mutilation, bride-burning, sexual slavery and forced sterilization.
It condemns rape, especially as a weapon of war.

<p>

Still, as critics have pointed out, the document cultivates a
terrible moral and philosophic blindness to the human dignity
of women.  In many ways, the document is a monument to the &quot;exaggerated
individualism&quot; which characterizes the radical feminist movement.
It sees the role of wife and mother as impediments to a woman's
self-realization while refusing to recognize the harms, such as
disease and poverty, that are caused by irresponsible sexual behavior.

<p>

To take the issues in the Beijing document one by one:

<p>

<h4>1. Women's Roles</h4>

<p>

Despite the fact that 70 percent of the world's women are wives
and mothers, the Beijing document barely considers them in this
capacity.  Positive comments on women in connection with the family
are stuffed into a single paragraph (number 30), which reads:

<p><blockquote>

<i>

&quot;Women play a critical role in the family.  The family is
the basic unit of society and as such should be strengthened.
It is entitled to receive comprehensive protection and support.
In different cultural, political and social systems, various
forms of the family exist.  The rights, capabilities and responsibilities
of family members must be respected.  Women make a great contribution
to the welfare of the family and to the development of society,
which is still not recognized or considered in its full importance.
The social significance of maternity, motherhood, and the role
of parents in the family and in the upbringing of children should
be acknowledged.  Maternity, motherhood, parenting and the role
of women in procreation must not be a basis for discrimination
nor restrict the full participation of women in society.  Recognition
should also be given to the important role often played by women in many 
countries in caring for other members of their family.&quot;

</i>

</blockquote><p>

This paragraph is one of the few passages in the document which
speaks of women in connection with the family.  Another mention
(barely a nod) is paragraph 245b which urges that women's life
experiences, &quot;including, but not limited to their experiences
of balancing work and family responsibilities as mothers, as professionals,
as managers and entrepreneurs,&quot; be included in media depictions.

<p>

Elsewhere in the document, marriage is mentioned in a negative
way as, for example, in the context of dowry problems.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Parents' rights were not<br>
completely overruled, but<br>
they were subordinated to<br>
'the best interests of the<br>
child.'
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<h4>2. The Family</h4>

<p>

While the March, 1995 Copenhagen Programme devoted an entire
section to &quot;the family,&quot; and the September, 1994 Cairo
Plan of Action included a chapter on &quot;the family,&quot; the
Beijing Platform for Action, the U.N.'s longest document discussing
women, almost completely ignores the subject. The only mention
of &quot;the family&quot; of any length in the Beijing Platform
of Action is in the same paragraph 30, mentioned above.

<p>

Before it begins discussing &quot;motherhood,&quot; that paragraph
says: &quot;The family is the basic unit of society and as such
should be strengthened.  It is entitled to receive comprehensive
protection and support.  In different cultural, political and
social systems, various forms of the family exist. The rights,
capabilities and responsibilities of family members must be respected....
The upbringing of children requires shared responsibility of parents,
women and men and society as a whole.&quot;

<p>

Paragraph 30 was one of the most hotly debated sections in the
document.  From the first preparatory committee meeting in Jakarta,
pro-life delegates struggled to guarantee language acknowledging
the importance of the family (in its traditional sense) both in
the lives of women and to society at large, as stated in the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights (1948).  Feminists, on the other hand,
insisted on using the phrase &quot;the family in all its forms&quot;
to allow for homosexual unions.  A compromise sentence -- &quot;In
different cultural, political and social systems, various forms
of the family exist&quot; -- was added in Beijing to take into
account the existence of single-parent families and extended families.
Even this compromise sentence, however, could be misinterpreted
to condone homosexual unions.  It could also leave the door open
for &quot;the whole village&quot; (or more precisely, the state)
to direct the upbringing of children.

<p>

&quot;Family&quot; is mentioned again (cursorily) in the Beijing
document (paragraph 93) as one responsibility among many in a
woman's life.  It is mentioned in paragraph 285, where the document
speaks of the family's role in promoting the equality of the 
&quot;girl-child&quot; and in paragraph 108c, where men are encouraged 
&quot;to share equally in childcare and household work and to provide 
financial support for their families even if they do not live with 
them.&quot; The few other mentions of &quot;family&quot; in the document
are very negative.  In paragraph 114a, for example, the family
is mentioned as the venue for battering, sexual abuse, marital
rape, female genital mutilation, and other acts of violence against
women.

<p>

<h4>3. Women's Health</h4>

<p>

The women's health section is the longest and one of the most
troubling.  It begins rhapsodically, with the statement, &quot;Women
have the right to the enjoyment of the highest attainable standard
of physical and mental health... Health is a state of complete
physical, mental, and social well-being, and not merely the absence
of disease or infirmity&quot; (paragraph 91).  To this it adds
(repeating Cairo) in paragraph 96: &quot;Reproductive health is
a state of complete physical, mental, and social well-being, and
not merely the absence of disease or infirmity, in all matters
relating to the reproductive system and to its functions and 
processes.&quot;

<p>

To the point of neglecting most health problems, the document
concentrates on sexual or reproductive health.  AIDS alone gets
roughly 20 paragraphs, whereas cardiac disease and cancer are
mentioned only once or twice.  The document almost completely
ignores the problem of tropical disease which decimates female
populations in the Third World.

<p>

<h4>4. Reproductive Rights</h4>

<p>

The Beijing Declaration (paragraph 17) asserts that &quot;[t]he
explicit recognition and reaffirmation of the right of all women
to control all aspects of their health, in particular their own
fertility, is basic to their empowerment.&quot;

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Lesbian 'rights' language<br>
was finally excluded as<br>
weary delegates looking<br>
for a few hours of sleep<br>
deleted all references<br>
to sexual orientation<br>
from the document.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

But the most stunning part of the Platform is its pronouncement
that women have a &quot;human right&quot; to control their own
sexuality and reproduction.  Paragraph 97 of the health section
declares that: &quot;The human rights of women include their right
to have control over and decide freely and responsibly on matters
related to their sexuality, including sexual and reproductive 
health.&quot;

<p>

Raising a woman's right to control her own sexuality and reproduction
to a &quot;human right&quot; is a considerable step beyond the
1993 Vienna Programme of Action's statement that &quot;reproductive
rights rest on the recognition of the basic right of all couples
and individuals to decide freely and responsibly the number, spacing
and timing of their children and to have the information and means
to do so.&quot;  It is also a considerable step beyond Cairo's
similar statement on the subject.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The Beijing document<br>
contains some positive<br>
aspects: it denounces<br>
forced prostitution,<br>
pornography, genital<br>
mutilation, bride-burning,<br>
sexual slavery and forced<br>
sterilization. It condemns<br>
rape, expecially as a<br>
weapon of war.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

The 1994 Cairo document had asserted that &quot;reproductive
rights embrace certain human rights that are already recognized
in national laws, international human rights documents and other
relevant U.N. consensus documents.&quot;  Moreover, the Beijing
Plan of Action had originally labelled controlling one's own fertility
&quot;a sexual right,&quot; but not &quot;a human right.&quot;
A woman's &quot;human right&quot; to control her sexual and reproductive
health could be understood to mean that she has a &quot;human
right&quot; to promiscuity, homosexuality and to abortion.

<p>

When this language was adopted in committee on September 10,
the Holy See was very concerned by what it saw as the invention
of a new &quot;human right.&quot;  At the conference and, more
recently, in the <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (September 21, 1995),
the Holy See delegation chief Mary Ann Glendon, an American and
professor of law at Harvard University, protested the Conference's
tampering with the Universal Declaration. &quot;All this is 
evidence,&quot; she said, &quot;of the increasing colonization of the 
great Universal Human Rights tradition by an impoverished U.S.-style 
libertarian rights dialectic whose features are (1) rights envisioned without 
corresponding individual or social responsibilities; (2) one's favorite 
rights (i.e., speech, property, etc.) touted as absolute while other
rights are ignored; (3) the rights-bearer is imagined as radically
autonomous and self-sufficient; and (4) the creation of new rights
which are often in conflict with one another (e.g., the right
to smoke versus a clean environment).&quot;

<p>

<h4>5. Abortion</h4>

<p>

Besides the disturbing paragraph 97, the Beijing document makes
no new inroads in promoting the legality of abortion.  Repeating
Cairo, the document says (paragraph 107k), &quot;In no case should
abortion be promoted as a means of family planning.&quot;  But
due to the precedent set at the 1994 Cairo conference, the term
&quot;reproductive rights&quot; in U.N. documents must now always
be understood to imply abortion in those countries where abortion
has been legalized.  Indeed, paragraph 107k continues by saying,
&quot;In circumstances where abortion is not against the law,
such abortions should be safe.&quot;

<p>

Despite the protests of pro-life delegates at both Cairo and
Beijing that abortion is never &quot;safe&quot; for the baby in
question, the Beijing document repeatedly condemns &quot;unsafe
abortions&quot; (which it defines as &quot;a procedure for terminating
an unwanted pregnancy either by persons lacking necessary skills
or in an environment lacking minimum medical standards&quot;).
For example, paragraph 95 lists &quot;unsafe abortion&quot; among
the consequences of early sexual experience, and paragraph 98
says that &quot;[u]nsafe abortions threaten the lives of a number
of women, presenting a serious public health problem.&quot; 
Paragraph 107k asks governments &quot;to deal with the health impact
of unsafe abortions as a major public health concern and to reduce
the recourse to abortions by increasing and improving family planning
services.&quot;

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The document is a monument<br>
to the 'exaggerated<br>
individualism' which<br>
characterizes the radical<br>
feminist movement.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

During the negotiations in Beijing, the draft document's several
mentions of unborn life were either struck down or severely weakened.
In each instance where the document formerly mentioned &quot;female
foeticide&quot; (paragraphs 40 ,41, 115bis, etc.), the term was
replaced by &quot;prenatal sex selection.&quot;  But paragraph
276c which condemns son preference and unethical practices such
as prenatal sex selection and female infanticide, still adds,
&quot;This is often compounded by the increasing use of technologies
to determine fetal sex resulting in the abortion of female fetuses.&quot;

<p>

Also notable is paragraph 107k which calls on states to &quot;consider
reviewing laws containing punitive measures against women who
have undergone illegal abortions.&quot;  This paragraph also states,
&quot;Prevention of unwanted pregnancies must always be given
the highest priority, and every attempt should be made to eliminate
the need for abortion.  Any measures or changes related to abortion
within the health system can only be determined at the national
or local level according to the national legislative process.&quot;
(Given the restrictions on pro-life legislation in this country,
one has to wonder whether the U.S. is in compliance with this
language.)

<p>

Paragraph 107k also states, &quot;In all cases, women should
have access to quality services for the management of complications 
arising from abortion.  Post-abortion counseling, education and 
family-planning services should be offered promptly, which will also 
help to avoid repeat abortions.&quot;

<p>

<h4>6. Parents' Responsibility for Children</h4>

<p>

Despite the fact that Article 26 of the United Nations' Universal
Declaration of Human Rights states, &quot;Parents have a prior
right to choose the kind of education that shall be given to their
children,&quot; the Beijing document hardly acknowledges parental
authority over children.  Indeed, at least 17 references to parental
responsibility for children were deleted from the draft document.

<p>

For example, there is no longer any reference to parents' rights
in paragraph 107m, which asks governments to &quot;[e]nsure that
girls have continuing access to necessary health and nutrition
information and services, as they mature, to facilitate a healthy
transition from childhood to adulthood.&quot;

<p>

Parental rights language was also removed from paragraph 109(1),
which approves condom use for male adolescents.  (Moreover, despite
strong objections voiced by Catholic and Muslim delegates, a paragraph
asking governments to &quot;encourage abstinence as responsible
behavior until marriage&quot; was swiftly discarded at the Beijing
conference, at the urging of the Canadian delegation.)

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Despite the fact that 70<br>
percent of the world's<br>
women are wives and mothers,<br>
the Beijing document barely<br>
considers them in this capacity.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

The only vestige of parental responsibility which remains in
the document relates to the &quot;direction and guidance&quot;
of children.  But this weak language still disregards parents,
leaving most decision-making responsibilities to the child, including
(possibly) the decision of abortion.

<p>

In the end, the key paragraph relating to parents' rights and
children's rights turned out to be paragraph 267.  This  paragraph
reads:

<p><blockquote>

<i>

&quot;The International Conference on Population and Development
recognized, in paragraph 7.3 of the Programme of Action, that
'full attention should be given to the promotion of mutually respectful
and equitable gender relations and particularly to meeting the
educational and service needs of adolescents to enable them to
deal in a positive and responsible way with their sexuality,'
taking into account the rights of the child to access to information,
privacy, confidentiality, respect and informed consent, as well
as the responsibilities, rights and duties of parents and legal
guardians to provide, in a manner consistent with the evolving
capacities of the child, appropriate direction and guidance in
the exercise by the child of the rights recognized in the Convention
on the Rights of the Child, and in conformity with the Convention
on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women.
In all actions concerning children, the best interests of the
child shall be a primary consideration.  Support should be given
to integral sexual education for young people with parental support
and guidance that stress the responsibility of males for their
own sexuality and fertility and that help them exercise their
responsibilities.&quot;

</i>

</blockquote><p>

Paragraph 108e  (about public health campaigns) takes the same
position, asking governments to:

<p><blockquote>

<i>

&quot;Prepare and disseminate accessible information...to ensure
that men and women, especially young people, can acquire knowledge about 
their health and especially information about sexuality and reproduction, 
taking into account the rights of the child to access to information,
privacy, confidentiality, respect and informed consent, as well
as the responsibilities, rights and duties of parents and legal
guardians to provide, in a manner consistent with the evolving
capacities of the child, appropriate direction and guidance in
the exercise by the child of the rights recognized in the Convention
on the Rights of the Child, and in conformity with the Convention
on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women.
In all actions concerning children, the best interests of the
child shall be a primary concern.&quot;

</i>

</blockquote><p>

<p>

<h4>7. Religion</h4>

<p>

There is only one paragraph in the Platform for Action dedicated
to the role of religion in women's lives. This paragraph (25bis),
which in its original form cast religion as oppressive to women
(i.e., associating it with extremism and violence), was reworked
to acknowledge that freedom of conscience and religion are recognized
by the Universal Declaration.

<p>

Paragraph 25bis now reads:

<p><blockquote>

<i>

&quot;Religion, spirituality and belief play a central role in the 
lives of millions of women and men -- in the way they live, in the 
aspirations that they have for the future. The right to freedom of 
thought, conscience and religion is unalienable
and must be universally enjoyed.  This right includes the freedom
to have or to adopt the religion or belief of their choice, either
individually or in community with others, in public or in private,
and to manifest their religion or belief in worship, observance,
practice and teaching, in order to realize equality, development
and peace there is a need to fully respect these rights and freedoms.
Religion, thought, conscience and belief may, and can, contribute
to fulfilling women's and men's moral, ethical and spiritual needs,
and to realizing their full potential in society.  However, it
is acknowledged that any form of extremism may have a negative
impact on women and can lead to violence and discrimination.&quot;

</i>

</blockquote>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The most stunning part<br>
of the Platform is its<br>
pronouncement that women<br>
have a 'human right' to<br>
control their own reproduction.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Within the Beijing Declaration, paragraph 12 includes &quot;the
right to freedom of thought, conscience, religion and belief,
thus contributing to the moral, ethical, spiritual and intellectual
needs of women and men&quot; among rights to be protected.  And
on occasion, the document also appends a phrase such as &quot;consistent
with religious and cultural values&quot; (paragraphs 74, 82f)
to qualify injunctions to action.
<p>

<center><h3>Concluding the Conference</h3></center>

<p>

The Platform for Action was hotly argued for twelve days, sometimes
long into the night.  Negotiations about sexual and reproductive
rights as human rights went on sporadically for three days. Canada's 
Ruth Archibald led the five-day drive to remove the document's 17 
references to parental rights.

<p>

But by far the most important and moving proceeding for pro-family
advocates came during the four-hour marathon following the formal
adoption of the Platform on September 15th in which 42 U.N. member
states registered reservations to the Platform.  (These 42 comprised
a full fifth of the organization's membership, not what critics
had at one time called &quot;a handful of Latin American and Moslem
states.&quot;)

<p>

These reservations were especially important because they countered
the claims made by members of the U.S. delegation -- Tim Wirth,
Geraldine Ferraro, Donna Shalala, and health negotiators Nils
Daulaire and Dottie Lamm -- who, throughout the conference, kept
insisting that things were going smoothly.  The reservations also
served to refute the networks, the <I>New York Times</I> and Ford
Foundation representative Frances Kissling (Catholics for a Free
Choice), who, in a consistent stream of disinformation, claimed
that the Vatican was caving in on contraceptives and condoms.

<p>

Announcing its reservations at the conference, the Holy See opted
out of the health section in its entirety, on the grounds that
it concentrated on sexual and reproductive health to the point
of almost failing to address other women's health needs, including
maternal mortality and morbidity. It objected to ambiguous terms
concerning unqualified control over sexuality and fertility which
might be interpreted as an endorsement of abortion and homosexuality.
With regard to the whole human rights section, the Holy See associated
itself with very little besides the quotations from existing human 
rights documents.  It asked that its definition of the word 
&quot;gender&quot;(biological sexual identity: male or female) be affixed 
to the document when it was printed.

<p>

Islamic states clarified that, for them, sexual rights apply
only within marriage, and that they had not agreed to anything
condoning abortion.  Several stressed that the Platform for Action
would be interpreted in their countries according to Sharia (Islamic)
law, especially in regard to inheritance for girls.  The Philippines
objected to treating reproductive rights as human rights.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The most important and<br>
moving proceeding came<br>
during the four-hour<br>
marathon following the<br>
formal adoption of the<br>
Platform in which 42 U.N.<br>
member states registered<br>
reservations to the Platform.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Malaysia said it would interpret &quot;family&quot; in the document
as the traditional family, and Ecuador said that the family is
the fundamental unit of society.  When the delegate from Niger
prepared to enter her reservation, she said publicly what many
developing country delegates had said earlier in private, &quot;We
hope that joining in the consensus will not be a pre-condition
for [donors'] financing of health programs.&quot;

<p>

In its final statement to the conference, the U.S. stressed its
commitment to the cause of women's empowerment and declared that
the Beijing Platform for Action would serve as a detailed map
for achieving women's equality, development and peace.  However,
neither the United States nor any of the other donor countries who so 
strongly backed the document have promised any new money for women's 
programs. They insisted that no new resources could be provided, turning
down the African and Latin American delegates who contended that
new and additional resources were needed to provide basic health
care to women, which was, for them, the overriding concern of
the conference.

<p>

<center><h3>Beijing's Implications</h3></center>

<p>

There is no doubt that the Beijing document will have consequences
for the family.  A year after Cairo, the first global survey made
by the U.N. examining its membership's progress to fulfill the
promises made in that conference's Plan of Action showed that
out of 53 nations surveyed, 46 have undertaken new policies to
implement the Cairo document.  The other seven nations were recorded
either as having lost ground in implementing the document or stayed
the same.  The U.N. Population Fund has also recently announced
that it increased its budget almost 21 percent in 1994 and another
17.6 percent in 1995, to a total of $312 million.  And plans are
already being considered for another U.N. women's meeting in 2000
and for a declaration of &quot;The Century of Women.&quot;

<p>

While the Beijing conference yielded few high points, one positive
result is that it drew together pro-family, conservative women
who for so long had resisted dealing with the U.N. due to their
general distaste for the organization.  In 1994, there were perhaps
two openly pro-life organizations among the NGOs at the U.N.,
but as recently as last April's PrepCom, there were 50.  The conference
in Beijing -- a long and very expensive journey from the US without
government or U.N. assistance -- drew over 200 women from close
to 150 conservative NGO organizations from 20 countries, including
Protestants, Catholics, Muslims and others.

<p>

Despite their late entrance and the fact that the feminists had
written most of the document, pro-family women became an important
part of the proceedings and undid a good deal of the damage that
preceded their arrival.  They supported pro-family delegates,
long-used to jeering and mockery.  They made the case for family
values on talk radio shows at home, telephoning from Beijing.
They even assisted delegates confused by inadequate U.N. translations,
patiently explaining code words like &quot;orientation&quot; and
&quot;gender&quot; to Third World delegates.  (Many Africans thought
that &quot;reproductive rights&quot; meant the right to have a
family.)

<p>

Most of all, these pro-family women were able to challenge U.S.
delegates on their partisanship, their lack of responsiveness
to the public, and their dearth of fidelity to traditional human
rights.  When the U.S. unfurled a banner demonstrating how closely
its commitments matched those of WEDO (a radical feminist NGO
led by Bella Abzug), conservative women raised another banner
made from a hotel bedsheet, pointing out where the U.S. had covered
its ears to conservative women.  So uncomfortable did the U.S.
delegation finally become with these new lobbyists that they called
in U.N. security guards to confiscate the conservatives' passes.

<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>-- Ellen Lukas

<p>

Ellen Lukas is a journalist with more than 30 years of experience
covering the U.N.  She represented the Family Research Council
at the U.N. Conference in Beijing, China.</i>

<p><hr><p>

