</DOCHDR>
<html>

<title>ON DRUGS: THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION'S CURIOUS SURRENDER</title>

<body>

<center>

<img src="/townhall/FRC/fampol/fampolrd.gif">

<h1>On Drugs</h1>
<h2><i>The Clinton Administration's Curious Surrender</i></h2>

</center>

<p>

<font size=+3>D</font>rug abuse among teenagers has risen significantly 
in recent years.  A nationwide survey by the National Institute on Drug 
Abuse (NIDA) found that between 1991 and 1994 annual marijuana use rose
from 6.2 percent to 13.0 percent among 8th graders, from 16.5 percent to 
30.4 percent among 10th	graders, and from 36.7 percent to 38.2 percent 
among 12th graders. Moreover, cocaine, crack, heroin, and LSD use among 
teenagers is also rising and may soon rival the high rates of the 1970s.[1]

<p>

Despite these trends, the Clinton Administration is leading an all-out 
retreat in the drug war. During the past two years, President Clinton 
has overseen the wholesale dismantling of government agencies that are at 
least partly responsible for the successes of the 1980s. The Clinton 
Administration has:

<p><ul>

<li>Dropped the drug war as one of the National Security Council's top 
priorities. It is now number 29 of 29.[2]

<p>

<li>Cut the drug czar's office by 80 percent from 146 to 25 personnel. 
It was partially restored by Congressional mandate.[3]

<p>

<li>Folded the State Department's Office of International Narcotics 
Matters into a potpourri organization that handles issues like labor, 
environment and population concerns.[4]

</ul>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
A growing number of experts believe<br>
the Clinton Administration's drug<br>
policy changes are at least partly<br>
responsible for the recent increase<br>
in youth drug use and addiction.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<ul>

<li>Left two key anti-drug positions vacant for at least six months: the 
drug czar and the position of Assistant Secretary of Defense for Drug 
Enforcement Policy and Support.[5]

<p>

<li>Cut military anti-drug efforts by signing an executive order 
drastically reducing the Pentagon's interdiction efforts. These cuts 
included 1,000 military positions devoted to anti-drug activities,[6] a 
move Rep. Charles Schumer (D-NY) called "a terrible mistake."[7]

<p>
	
<li>Cut drug interdiction funds for the Customs Service and the DEA. 
Today,	even though 70 percent of all cocaine comes to the U.S. via Mexico, 
the Customs Service does not routinely search for drugs inside semi-trailers 
crossing the border.[8]

<p>

<li>Reduced mandatory minimum sentences for drug traffickers.[9]

<p>

<li>Recommended, during his first-year budget, cuts in drug education 
(26 percent) and enforcement (15 percent).[10] Drug Czar Lee Brown learned 
of the proposed	cuts from an article in a newspaper.[11]

<p>

<li>Recommended merging the DEA with the FBI as part of the National 
Performance Review.[12]

<p>

<li>Cut 355 DEA agents and 102 personnel from the Justice Department's 
organized crime drug enforcement task force.[13]

<p>

<li>Cut the Coast Guard's drug interdiction budget by $14.6 million.[14]

<p>

<li>Terminated the DEA's drug kingpin program, which tracks international 
drug lords with the intent of bringing them to justice.

<p>

<li>Published a	report endorsing needle exchange programs intended to 
reduce the spread of AIDS and encouraged local governments to begin needle 
exchange programs.

</ul>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
A successful war on drugs must<br>
balance treatment with prevention<br>
and interdiction. The Clinton<br>
strategy is unbalanced.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<ul>

<li>Created DEA's mobile enforcement team (MET) program, which takes 
agents off international beats and puts them in squad cars with local 
police. International drug smuggling, the intended target of the DEA, has 
not abated.[15]

<p>

<li>Cut drug treatment and prevention budgets by $100 and $130 million 
respectively.[16]

<p>

<li>Disbanded Operation Snow-Cap, which assigned DEA agents to assist 
anti-drug police in cocaine-producing nations.

</ul><p>

<center><h3>Bearing Responsibility</h3></center>

<p>

While it is certainly appropriate for policymakers to make changes that 
will improve the effectiveness of legitimate government programs (and these 
changes	will sometimes take the form of budget cuts, departmental 
consolidation and new priorities) a growing number of experts believe the 
Clinton Administration's drug policy changes are at least partly responsible 
for the recent increase in youth drug use and addiction.  For example, former 
First Lady Nancy Reagan told a Congressional committee in March 1995, "Why is 
it we no longer hear the drumbeat of condemnation against drugs coming from 
our leaders and our culture?  Is it any	wonder drug use has started climbing 
and dramatically so?"[17]

<p>

Former drug czar William Bennett stated, there is "no viable effort by the 
Clinton Administration to prevent the complete disintegration of foreign 
supply control.  This is an unconscionable abdication.  We face the real 
prospect of foreign nations permitting the unchallenged production and 
shipment of illegal drugs to the U.S."[18]

<p>

Former Drug Enforcement Administration director Robert Bonner stated, "I 
believe	that there has been a near total absence of presidential leadership 
by President Clinton in the fight to turn back illegal drug use in this 
country...It [the Administration] clearly fails to promote an increased 
awareness of the dangers of drug abuse, arguably encourages it...The 
Clinton	Administration's national drug strategy has failed miserably, and 
indeed it is a tragedy. The President must reverse this trend and start 
leading our nation's anti-drug efforts."[19]

<p>

Rep. Charles Rangel (D-NY) said, "I've been in Congress for over two 
decades, and I have never, never, never seen a president who cares 
less about this issue."[20]

<p>

Rep. John Conyers (D-MI) told Lee Brown during the drug czar's 
confirmation hearings, "Either the president is with you, or he has just 
given you a chair at the cabinet level...If it is the latter, you are 
getting ready to be the biggest fall guy in the Clinton Administration...We 
might as well close [the drug office] down and stop the pretense."[21]

<p>

Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) spokesman Wayne Roques, a 25-year 
veteran of the drug war, states: "The drug culture, sensing a weakening 
in our national resolve, has reared its ugly head and embarked on a 
well-financed, unconscionable campaign to legalize drugs."[22]

<p>

Attorney General Janet Reno has heard enough of the criticism of the 
Clinton anti-drug efforts.  She stated, "I would just suggest that it 
has come time to stop the political labeling of this fight and all of us 
join together in one common-sense, concentrated	effort that goes after 
the traffickers, that goes after the violence spawned by the drugs but 
provides education, prevention and treatment in a way that can truly make 
a difference."[23]

<p>

The nation's chief law enforcement officer makes a good point, but the 
Clinton Administration's actions send a very different message.  They 
represent a major philosophical shift from the Reagan/Bush years.

<p>

Presidential candidate Bill Clinton told the Democratic National 
Convention in July 1992, "[President Bush] hasn't fought a real war on 
crime and drugs, I will."[24] He promised to combine tough law 
enforcement with expanded treatment and prevention programs.  He also 
pledged to appoint a strong drug czar.[25]

<p>

Clinton's longstanding commitment to drug treatment is evidenced in his 
1995 National Drug Strategy.  He states: "The National Drug Control 
Strategy...confirms...my priorities for addressing this nation's 
continuing drug problem...This strategy gives those who	have fallen 
prey to drugs the opportunity to change their behavior."  His strategy 
focuses on treatment.[26]

<p>
	
The President told <I>Rolling Stone</I> reporters that drug treatment 
is "a big issue."[27] He explained his intent to "change the focus of 
interdiction to work on the roots of the exports to the United States" 
and "we decided to go ahead and put drug treatment into the 
health-care bill."[28]

<p>

Former drug czar Bennett points out that a successful war on drugs must	
balance treatment with prevention and interdiction.  The Clinton strategy 
is unbalanced.

<p>

<center><h3>Some Curious Appointees</h3></center>

<p>

Clinton appointees have orchestrated a campaign to liberalize the 
government's war on drugs.

<p>

For example, Clinton's first Surgeon General Joycelyn Elders created a 
firestorm when she responded to a question at a National Press Club 
luncheon by stating, "I do feel	that we would markedly reduce our crime 
rate if drugs were legalized."[29]

<p>

Her comments evoked reactions from many sectors. Senator Bob Dole 
(R-KS) said, "Americans must be wondering if the Surgeon General 
is hazardous to our health."[30] But Baltimore Mayor Kurt Schmoke 
applauded Elders: "I think what the Surgeon General said was 
absolutely courageous and correct; there should be a study."[31]

<p>

While President Clinton sought to distance himself from Elders' 
comments, the Clinton Justice Department issued a study recommending 
reduction in mandatory minimum drug sentences.[32]

<p>

The DOJ's report, "An Analysis of Non-Violent Drug Offenders with 
Minimal	Criminal Histories,"[33] found that low-level drug law 
violators are much less likely to commit another crime than high-level 
defendants and that sentence length had no effect on recidivism	rates. 
The study recommends that the money spent on jailing low-level drug 
offenders could be better spent on other criminal justice needs such as 
more police.  

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The Clinton Justice Department<br>
issued a study recommending<br>
reduction in mandatory minimum<br>
sentences.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

But the study has a number of problems. A "significant number" (43 
percent) of the 16,316 federal inmates in this study were non-citizens 
with unknown criminal histories.  This fact should have eliminated these 
inmates from the study.[34] In addition, the study failed to consider 
the impact that incarcerating low-level	drug sellers has on the illicit 
drug market.  Incarcerating convicted drug dealers sends a clear message 
-- drug trafficking has a price.  No one knows how many potential 
traffickers consider the price and turn to alternative employment.

<p>

Not only did the Clinton Administration call for drug legalization, 
but it also issued a 1993 report advocating needle-exchange programs 
even though these programs fail.  Before joining the Clinton 
Administration, Dr. Philip Lee was the principal investigator for a 
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention study released in September 
1993 which analyzed 37 needle-exchange programs.[35] The report, "The 
Public Health Impact of Needle Exchange Programs in the United States 
and Abroad," concluded[36] that "needle exchanges neither increase 
nor decrease levels of inject[able] drug use,"[37] and stated that 
"studies of the effect of needle exchange programs on HIV infection 
rates do not...and probably cannot provide clear evidence that 
needle exchange programs decrease HIV infection rates."[38]

<p>

Despite these findings, the report recommends:

<p><ul>

<li>"[T]he U.S. government should repeal the ban on federal funding 
of needle exchanges."

<p>

<li>States should repeal their prescription and/or paraphernalia laws 
banning possession of needles.

<p>

<li>Local communities should encourage the wider availability of 
sterile needles by allowing pharmacists to sell or exchange them.

</ul><p>

The Clinton Administration has encouraged needle-exchange programs, 
alleging that they will slow the advance of the virus that causes AIDS. 
Such programs, however, are not effective.

<p>

The much-publicized "Needle Park" (Platzspitz) experiment in Zurich, 
Switzerland was canceled after Swiss authorities concluded that	
needle exchanges promote crime, AIDS, drug abuse, and prostitution. 
After authorities closed the park, drug dealers and addicts moved the 
drug market to a formerly scenic bridge (named Lettensteg). The 
bridge was soon littered with thousands of discarded and probably 
contaminated needles and syringes. In February 1995, Swiss police 
fought a series of fierce gun battles to terminate Lettensteg's drug 
culture operation.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Incarcerating convicted drug<br>
dealers sends a clear message<br>
-- drug trafficking has a price.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

A government-sponsored needle exchange program in New York City has 
met a similar fate. "Ever since the lower east side Harm Reduction 
Center, a needle exchange program, began operating in a storefront 
in a residential population of working poor, our community has 
witnessed drug abuse not seen since Operation Pressure Point cleared 
the area of drugs in the 1980s," one resident observed. "You can 
receive your government-sponsored clean needles (there is no limit 
to the number), rob and steal to get money for drugs (or sell your 
clean needles), buy cocaine in storefronts or heroin on any corner, 
then leave behind a pool of blood, dirty syringes, glassine bags, 
alcohol swabs and bottle caps....Statistics on the spread of AIDS 
cannot be the only criteria for measuring the success of the 
program."[39]

<p>

<center><h3>Interdiction Failures</h3></center>

<p>

The Clinton Administration has also failed to sustain an effective 
international drug suppression effort.

<p>

Brian Sheridan, Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for Drug 
Enforcement Policy and Support, told a House Committee in October 
1994 that the Pentagon recommended $135 million in counterdrug 
budget cuts.[40] The Pentagon has also cut at least 1,000 military 
personnel from drug interdiction programs and has terminated 24 
programs because of "insufficient utility."[41] Sheridan explained, 
"We must recognize that illicit drug use is a deep-seated social 
problem which, like the problems of crime and inner-city poverty, 
will have to be addressed by all Americans over the long-term."[42]
	
<p>

An equal threat is posed by drug lords in South America. The 
Colombia-based Cali cartel is a cocaine distribution network which 
includes a corporate headquarters and franchises throughout the United 
States.  It has effectively overwhelmed the Customs Service, Coast 
Guard and the DEA. It employs sophisticated production,	transportation 
and marketing efforts.  Some laboratories are the size of industrial 
factories, operating with the unofficial endorsement of host 
governments. There are ten entry point/distribution hubs in the U.S. 
The Cali kingpins or their operations chiefs oversee regional directors, 
who in turn supervise regional "cells."  And the cocaine comes to 
American shores	through contract carriers via air, land and sea.  They 
employ cargo jets, large tractor trailers which are seldom inspected 
at the Mexican border, and ships filled to the brim with tons of 
cocaine.  For example, a 14-ton shipment of cocaine was found hidden 
inside concrete fence posts and bound for Longview, Texas via Miami.[43]

<p>

DEA director Thomas Constantine told the House Judiciary Subcommittee 
on Crime, "[O]ur crime situation is controlled by foreign criminals. 
Marketing decisions made in Cali, Colombia or the highlands of the 
Golden Triangle have a direct impact on the drug trade in the 
streets of New York or the waterfront of Miami.  Highly organized, 
technologically-advanced criminal groups have come to dominate the 
production and distribution of heroin and cocaine destined for the 
U.S."[44]

<p>

Although Clinton's DEA chief, Thomas Constantine, pledged at his 
confirmation hearing to promote "the most effective [anti-drug] 
enforcement possible under the rule of law,"  Senator Orrin Hatch 
(R-UT) cautioned, "Some people are concerned there's a different 
attitude down there [at the White House] to legalize drugs."[45]
	
<p>

During Constantine's watch, the DEA has experienced serious personnel 
and budget cuts. He shut down operations for three weeks in early 
1995 to reorganize.  Constantine has also canceled Operation Snow-Cap, 
which had slowed the production and shipment of cocaine in the source 
countries. He has discontinued the TKO kingpin operation, which 
tracked drug lords and brought them to justice.  And now he has 
directed DEA agents to turn away from overseas and focus on the 
grass-roots level, helping police departments with street-level 
suppression.  The mobile enforcement team (MET)	program places teams 
of DEA agents in communities to assist police departments.[46]

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The Clinton Administration<br>
issued a report advocating<br>
needle-exchange programs even<br>
though these programs fail.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

These radical changes jeopardize the U.S.'s international interdiction 
effort and severely threaten the morale of an organization that has 
long defended our borders.  FBI director Louis Freeh told a House 
Committee on March 30, 1995, "If law enforcement is to stem or even 
slow the flood of drugs into this country, we must have a strong and 
effective presence overseas."[47]

<p>

To add insult to injury, DEA agents are subjected to Justice 
Department briefings that show how to properly use syringes to 
inject illicit drugs.  This training is part of the Clinton 
Administration's mandatory AIDS awareness training for federal 
employees.

<p>

Mr. Clinton promised to hire a strong drug czar. In April 1993, 
Clinton elevated the drug czar to the cabinet level, explaining, "I 
believe drug abuse is as serious a problem as we have in America."[48] 
Then he slashed the czar's staff 80 percent.

<p>

Clinton spokeswoman Alice Rivlin, deputy director of OMB, told a 
Congressional budget hearing, "It is not that drug policy is less 
important...On the contrary it is more important...The problem has 
been a lack of leadership, not the size of the staff."[49]

<p>

Selecting Brown does not match the President's promise to hire "a 
strong drug czar" or seek the right "leader."  Brown, a former New 
York police commissioner, left that post under the shadow of the 
Crown Heights riot.

<p>

After becoming drug czar, Brown was excluded from the White House 
communication loop.  In July 1993, White House budget officials 
accepted a major cut in anti-drug programs without consulting Brown. 
He didn't know about the arrangement until he read it in <i>The 
Washington Post</i>.[50]

<p>

<center><h3>Bad Company</h3></center>

<p>

President Clinton has surrounded himself with many counselors, but 
their wisdom with regard to drug issues deserves scrutiny.

<p>

Consider some Clinton advisors and their views on drugs:

<p><ul>

<li><b><i>Clinton's Minister.</i></b> On Sunday, April 10, 1994	the 
Clintons were at church like millions of other Americans.  That morning 
their regular pastor, the Reverend Walter Shropshire of the Foundry 
United Methodist Church, said he believed the government could create 
"a safer environment for all of us" if now-illegal drugs were legalized. 
He later explained, "I happen to have the belief that one of the things 
that we need to re-examine in our current society is the...legalization 
of some drugs.  And my belief is that if the economic portions could be 
cut out of the cocaine and heroin traffic, it might be possible to make 
a safer	environment for all of us."[51]

<p>

<li><b><i>Clinton's College Mentor.</i></b> Not only are some of Mr. 
Clinton's spiritual advisors sympathetic to legalization but so are 
some of his former academic mentors.  His former Yale law professor, 
Steven Duke, co-author of a 1993 book <i>America's Longest War: 
Rethinking Our Tragic Crusade Against Drugs</i>, advocates legalizing 
cocaine, including crack, marijuana and heroin.[52]

<p>

<li><b><i>Clinton's Campaign Advisor.</i></b> Mathea Falco was 
recruited by the Clinton/Gore campaign to advise on drug policy 
issues. She is the president of Drug Strategy, a non-profit 
organization funded by pro-legalization billionaire George Soros, who 
gave Falco's organization a reported $2 million in 1994.[53] Drug 
Strategy is a drug policy think-tank that supports the legalization 
of marijuana.

<p>

During the mid-1970's, Falco was a special assistant to the president 
of the Drug Abuse Council, Inc. and testified in Congress on narcotics 
abuse favoring a "broad" reassessment of drug policy and the review 
of the feasibility of decriminalizing marijuana	and "possibly" cocaine. 
She subsequently served as an Assistant Secretary of State for 
international narcotics under President Carter.[54]

<p>

According to the pro-drug periodical <i>High Times</i>, Falco worked 
closely with Peter Bourne, President Carter's drug policy chief who 
fell from power after he was found to have snorted cocaine at a 
National Organization for the Reform of	Marijuana Laws (NORML) 
party.[55] The magazine told its March 1993 audience that Falco believes 
drug interdiction does not work and that she would support medical use 
of marijuana and needle	exchange.  She was thought to be a candidate 
for the drug czar's job.[56]

</ul>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
The Clinton Administration<br>
has also failed to sustain<br>
an effective international<br>
drug suppression effort.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<ul>

<li><b><i>Clinton's Advisors Reviewing DEA's Performance.</i></b> 
The Clinton Administration hired Mark Kleiman and Peter	Reuter to 
review the performance of the DEA.[57]

<p>

Kleiman is an associate professor at Harvard University's Kennedy 
School of Government and author of <i>Against Excess</i>, which includes 
an endorsement of marijuana legalization.[58] He was once a drug 
policy analyst for the Department of Justice and says that the 
primary goal of drug policy should be to limit the harms drug users 
do to themselves and the resulting harms to others.

<p>

According to <i>High Times</i>, Kleiman advocates user licenses 
for alcohol and pot and served as a graduate advisor for psychedelic 
researcher Rick	Doblin.[59] He spoke at a 1990 conference entitled 
"Regulation or Prohibition: Psychedelics in the	1990s."  In April 
1993, Kleiman spoke at a conference sponsored by NORML stating, "The 
hardest, intellectually, the hardest problem, I think, facing American 
Drug Policy is how to make the psychedelics available for their 
beneficial uses to people who can get benefit from them without	
increasing use under dangerous conditions, and abuse."[60]

<p>

In October 1994, John Carnevale, director of Office of Planning and 
Budget, Executive Office of the President, Office of National Drug 
Control Policy, defended the drug czar's decision to employ Kleiman's 
services. His organization, BOTEC, Inc., Carnevale said "has conducted 
a number of important studies over the past few years for ONDCP, 
especially in the area of monitoring the emerging heroin situation...At	
the current time, BOTEC's work, for whose timeliness and quality we have 
very high regard, continues to be the analysis of heroin use trends."[61] 
Kleiman is listed by Lee Brown as one of the many "expert individuals" 
to the drug czar for the 1995 National Drug Control Strategy.[62]

<p>

<li><b><i>Clinton's White House Staff.</i></b> All White House staff 
members require security clearances. Use of illegal drugs has long 
been a disqualification for a security clearance.

<p>

One of the first indications that drugs would be viewed differently 
by the Clinton Administration was the conduct of drug-testing for 
incoming presidential staff members.  The Clinton White House waived 
drug-testing until February 15, 1993 -- almost four weeks into the 
new administration.[63] By comparison, the Bush Administration 
required all new presidential aides to obtain negative test results 
before they could start work at the White House.[64]

<p>

The problem with staff drug testing continued for more than a year. 
In July 1994, then-press secretary Dee Dee Myers confirmed that one 
third of the White House staff still did not have "permanent 
passes."[65] This indicated a possible problem with drug-testing 
compliance. She admitted to being one of those without a pass, explaining 
she didn't have time to complete the paperwork.[66]

<p>

Director of White House Administration Patsy Thomasson oversees the 
security passes.  She once served at the right hand of an Arkansas 
investor, Dan Lasater, who pleaded guilty to federal drug charges. Her 
past association with a drug felon compelled the Senate to vote 98-0 
in June 1994 to require the president to certify that Thomasson	has 
no history of drug abuse.[67]

</ul>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
One of the first indications<br>
that drugs would be viewed<br>
differently by the Clinton<br>
Administration was the conduct<br>
of drug-testing for incoming<br>
presidential staff members.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<ul>

The suspicions about the White House staff linger. For example, the 
<i>Washington Times</i> reported in January 1995 that White House 
staffers have been seen	using drugs at parties around Washington. 
The paper quoted an unnamed source, "There's this private little 
social scene and everybody just assumes that no one's going to 
tattletale." Allegedly, one of the drug-using staff members works on 
the White House's National Security Council.[68]

<p>

Newt Gingrich ignited a firestorm on December 4, 1994 when he said, "I 
had a senior law enforcement official tell me that, in his judgment, 
up to a quarter of the White House Staff, when they first came in, 
had used drugs in the last four or five years...it's very clear that 
they had huge problems getting people through security clearances 
because they kept bringing people in who had a lot of things that 
weren't very easy to clear."[69]

<p>

White House Chief of Staff Leon	Panetta rebutted the allegation. "There 
is no one in the White House who uses drugs."  But according to 
the <i>Washington Times</i>, White House staffers who frequent the 
Oval Office were seen "passing around joints [marijuana cigarettes]" 
at a local party.[70]

<p>

An unnamed senior administration official said that Gingrich got 
the number right but the time period wrong.  He said that a quarter 
of the White House staff admitted to using illegal drugs at some point 
in the past, however, that's well below the national average of almost 
40 percent.  Miss Myers noted, "Only one employee has failed a random 
drug test and that employee was a career person in a non-policy	
role."[71]

<p>

As recently as March 27, 1995, Miss Thomasson told a Senate subcommittee 
that 11	White House staffers are in a special random drug-testing 
program because of concerns about "recent drug use."  She also 
acknowledged that volunteers without adequate security clearances have 
been given access to sensitive areas in the White House and added that 
92.2 percent of eligible staff members had received permanent entrance 
passes.[72]

</ul><p>

<center><h3>Other Pro-Legalization Allies</h3></center>

<p>

The Clinton Administration's retreat in the drug war has encouraged 
a wide range of pro-legalization advocates, including:

<p><ul>

<li><b><i>Ethan Nadelmann.</i></b> He heads a pro-drug organization, 
the Lindesmith Center, which is heavily funded by billionaire George 
Soros.[73] Soros is pushing the "harm reduction" agenda, which is 
widely viewed as a first step toward legalization.  Soros's goal "is 
to invigorate and support a broader debate on drug policy" and to shift 
from drug war to "drug peace."[74]

<p>

Nadelmann advances the notion that illegal drug use is a private issue 
and predicts that "in another five or ten years maybe the right over 
one's consciousness, the right to possess and consume drugs, may be 
as powerfully and as widely understood as the other rights of Americans	
are."[75]

<p>

Nadelmann told <i>Reason</i> magazine, "The replacement of the 
Bush Administration with the Clinton Administration was generally a 
good thing.  It brought in a lot of new blood, new thinking. Lee 
Brown is not what I would call a desirable drug czar, but he's no 
William Bennett, either. There's more room for consideration of 
alternatives."[76]

<p>

<li><b><i>Rep. Barney Frank (D-MA).</i></b> Congressman Frank told 
a 1994 NORML conference, "I think we ought to make smoking marijuana 
legal."[77] He also told a Harvard Law School conference titled, 
"Crime, Drugs, Health and Prohibition," that the government spends 
too much money to stop drug trafficking.[78] He told a radio 
audience, "We should give the money to drug treatment and local 
cops."[79]

<p>

<li><b><i>Eric Sterling.</i></b> He serves as president of the 
nonprofit Criminal Justice Policy Foundation and is a former counsel 
to the U.S. House Subcommittee on Crime and principal aide in 
developing parts of the Comprehensive Crime Control Act of 1984 and 
the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986.

<p>

He currently works with the Centers for Disease Control and the 
D.C. Commission on Public Health and has been honored by the U.S. 
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and the U.S. Postal 
Inspection Service. Sterling told a 1991 NORML conference, "Hi,	
I'm Eric Sterling and I'm a 15-year member of NORML and I'm really 
glad to be here to talk to so many of you...How many of you are 
stoned now?  Show of hands.  Honestly, how many of you are stoned 
now...about a quarter.  And I ask that question because I used to 
get stoned at NORML conferences	and it was my favorite, favorite 
times [sic] to get stoned."[80]

</ul>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
White House staffers have<br>
been seen using drugs at<br>
parties around Washington.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<ul>

Mr. Sterling was a guest speaker at the 6th Annual Conference on 
Drug-Free Schools and Communities.  Some attendees called for his 
removal based on his open advocacy of drug use.

<p>

He continues to speak out for drug legalization. For example, he 
was a guest speaker at the 1993 Fifth Annual Hemp Freedom Rally in 
Massachusetts and spoke at a pro-pot rally in front of the White House 
on January 21, 1993.  He led the crowd in chanting "Inhale to the 
Chief."

<p>

<li><b><i>Organizations like the Drug Policy Foundation.</i></b> 
Michigan drug czar Robert Peterson observed, "Groups like [the] 
Drug Policy Foundation are run by three-piece-suited guys, not dope 
smokers, and they say they don't support legalization, that they're 
just studying alternatives...But I think that's just to put a 
respectable front on what they are really doing, lobbying for 
legalization...I got hold of the agenda for one of their meetings, 
and it included discussions of money laundering and bank secrecy."[81]

<p>

The DPF	will award more than $1 million in grants to promote drug 
legalization programs. For example, in February 1995, DPF awarded 
$25,000 to Cannabis Action Network, which advocates marijuana use; 
$15,000 to NORML for National Medical Marijuana Day; and $3,000 to 
the National AIDS Brigade which	promotes needle exchange programs.[82]

</ul><p>

<center><h3>Conclusion</h3></center>

<p>

The Clinton Administration's actions and its advisors' reputations 
suggest a general lack of commitment to the drug war.  With drug abuse 
on the rise, the President must lead the nation in an all-out effort 
to turn the tide of drugs away from our shores and especially away from 
our children.

<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>- by Robert L. Maginnis<br>
FRC Policy Analyst</i>

<p><hr><p>

