<title>Top Ten Stats of Week -- Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"></a>
<h2>The <i>Right</i> Numbers</h2>Compiled from the 1990 Long Form Census information<p>
<h3>Top Ten Facts for the Week of December 6</h3></center>

<hr><P>

<b>1.</b>   Rate of <b>violent victimization</b> for black males:
<p><dl>
	Black males age 16 to 19 sustained one violent crime for:<br>
<center>	<dt>		10 persons in 1973<br>
			8 in 1992</center></dt>
	Black males age 12 to 15 sustained one violent crime for:<br>
<center><dt>			10 persons in 1973<br>
			14 in 1992</center></dt></dl>
<p>
Source: "National Crime Victimization Survey: Young Black Male Victims", Bureau of Justice Statistics Crime Data Brief, December, 1994.
<p><hr><p>
<b>2.</b>   For <b>union and non-union families</b> with one or more child under 18, <b>mean family income is</b>:
<p><center>
		$40,014 for families where neither parents belongs to a union<br>
		$54,200 for families where one or more parent is a union member
</center><p>
Source: 1994 Current Population Survey, U.S. Bureau of Census
<p><hr><p>
<b>3.  Army and Navy manpower</b>:
<center>
<table border>
<tr>
<th>Year</th><th>Army</th><th>Navy</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>1950</td><td>593,000</td><td>381,000</td>
</tr>
<tr><td>1965</td><td>969,000</td><td>670,000</td>
 </tr>
<tr>
<td>1980</td><td>777,000</td><td>527,000</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>1993</td><td>572,000</td><td>510,000</td>
</tr></table></center>
<p>
Source: "Department of Defense Manpower", Table No. 553, <i>1994 Statistical Abstract</i><p><hr><p>
<b>4.</b> National <b>Health Expenditures</b> as a percentage of GDP:
<P><center>
		1960:   5.3%<br>
		1975:   8.4%<br>
		1993: 13.9%<br>
	</center><P>
Source: "National Health Expenditures", Table No. 147, <i>1994 Statistical Abstract</i>, U.S. Bureau of the Census.
<p><hr><p>

<b>5 </b> Percent of <b>Health Care Expenditures</b> as <b>Total Consumer Unit Expenditures</b>:
<P><center>
1984 -- 4.8%<br>
1985 -- 4.7%<br>
1986 -- 4.8%<br>
1987 -- 4.6%<br>
1988 -- 5.0%<br>
1989 -- 5.1%<br>
1990 -- 5.2%<br>
1991 -- 5.2%<br>
1992 -- 5.5%<br>
</center><P>
Source: <i>1994 Statistical Abstract</i>, Table #164.
<p><hr><p>
<b>6.</b> Number of <b>Daily Newspapers</b>:
<P><center>
1980 -- 1,745<br>
1985 -- 1,676<br>
1990 -- 1,611<br>
1992 -- 1,570<br>
</center><p>
Source: <i>1994 Statistical Abstract</i>, Table #903
<p><hr><p>

<b>7. City Employees</b> (in thousands):
<p><center>
1980 -- 2,561<br>
1990 -- 2,642<br>
1991 -- 2,662<br>
1992 -- 2,665<br>
</center><p>
Source: <i>1994 Statistical Abstract</i>, Table #903
<p><hr><p>

<b>8.</b> Public Elementary and Secondary <b>School Enrollments</b> (in thousands):
<p><center>
1980 -- 27,647<br>
1990 -- 29,878
</center><p>
Source: <i>1994 Statistical Abstract</i>,  Table #242
<p><hr><p>
<b>9.</b> President Bush Vote among <b>Republican Men and Women</b>, 1988 and 1992:
<center><p><table border>
<tr>
<th></th><th>1988</th><th>1992</th><th>Difference</th>
</tr>
<td>Republican Men</td><td>91%</td><td>71%</td><td><center>-20</center></td>
</tr>
 <tr>
 <td>Republican Women</td><td>90%</td><td>74%</td><td><center>-16</center></td>
</tr></table><p>
</center>Source: Voter Research and Surveys<p><hr><p><b>10.</b> Current <b>Members of Congress</b> whose previous <b>occupations</b> were:
<p><center>
	Lawyers: 		225<br>
	Law Enforcement: 	11
</center><p>
Source: <i>Congressional Quarterly</i>, November 12, 1994, Supplement 11.
