<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>3.</b> Population <b>65 and over</b> from 1980 projected to 2000:
<P><center>
<table border><tr>
<th></th><td>1980</td><td>1990</td><td>1992</td><td>2000</td>
</tr><tr>
<td>Population (thousands)</td><td>25,549</td><td>31,079</td><td>32,285</td><td>35,322</td>
</tr></table></center><P>




<font size="-1">Statistical Abstract of the United States, 1994.  Table #47.</font>
<p><hr><p>

<b>4.</b> Percentage of people in state <b>without telephones</b>, lowest and highest:
<p><center>
		Minnesota &#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;	  2.4%<br>	
		Mississippi &#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;	12.6%	
</center><p><hr><p>

<b>5.</b> Growth of <b>Computers in School</b> from 1985 to 1993:

<P><center><table border>
<tr>
<th></th><td>1984-1985</td><td>1992-1993</td>
</tr><tr>
<td>Percent of schools with Microcomputers</td><td>77.7%</td><td>97.4%</td>
</tr><tr>
<td>Number of students to Microcomputers, includes schools with no 
micros</td><td>62.7</td><td>12.2</td>
</tr></table></center>


<font size="-1">Statistical Abstract of the United States, 1994.  Table #252.</font>
<p><hr><p>

<b>6.</b> Anglers and Hunters, 1991 (thousands):
<p><center>
<table border>
