Figures are based on data released by the Administrative Eligibility 
and Benefit Client Databases maintained by the Division of Family Development 
(NJDFD) of New Jersey's Department of Human Services in Trenton.  Data on birth 
rates prior to August 1992 or after November 1994 have yet to be compiled by 
NJDFD.  For a more complete accounting of New Jersey's birth statistics 
after implementation of the family cap, see &quot;The Impact of New Jersey's 
Family Cap on Out-of-Wedlock Births and Abortions,&quot; by Robert Rector, 
Heritage Foundation, September 6, 1995.
<p>
<li>Figures are state findings, reported by Dr. Rudolf Myers of the New 
Jersey Department of Human Services, and have not yet been corroborated 
by the independent evaluation study at Rutgers University.
<p>
<li>While births have dropped sharply in New Jersey since implementation 
of the cap, the available data indicate that the reduction in births was 
not accompanied by a real increase in either the abortion rate or the raw 
number of abortions.  For additional data, see &quot;The Impact of New 
Jersey's Family Cap on Out-of-Wedlock Births and Abortions,&quot; by 
Robert Rector, Heritage Foundation, September 6, 1995; &quot;The Straight 
Story on New Jersey: Births, Abortions, and the Family Cap,&quot; by 
Michael Schwartz, Life Advocacy Alliance, 1995 (copies available from 
the Family Research Council); and &quot;The Update on New Jersey: Beware 
a Rush to Judgment,&quot; by Jennifer E. Marshall, Family Research Council, 
1995.
