<html>

<title>KIDS HOPE USA: A VISION FOR CHURCHES AND CHILDREN</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">

<h2>KIDS HOPE USA:<br>
A VISION FOR<br>
CHURCHES AND CHILDREN</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by<br>
Dr. Virgil Gulker</i></center>

<p>

<i>The following speech was presented at the Family Research Council's
&quot;World Without Welfare&quot; symposium, held at the Willard
Hotel in Washington, D.C. on Dec. 13, 1995.</i>

<p>

My wife overheard someone recently call me an expert on the care
and nurture of children.  She was quite amused by that comment.
She simply smiled and walked away, and we haven't talked about
it since.

<p>

If your wife is like my wife, she remembers those times when we
have done anything but illustrate expertise in parenting.  I recall
the time, for example, when I disciplined my 4-year-old, and,
following the discipline, realized that I had made a mistake.
I had disciplined her for something that I had misinterpreted.
So I got down on my knees and put my hands on her little shoulders
and said, &quot;Emily, Daddy was wrong.  Will you forgive Daddy?&quot;
And Emily looked me in the eye and said, &quot;Sure, Daddy. I
forgive you lots.&quot;  I think all of you can relate to that
at some level.

<p>

I have two passions.  One is children and the other is the church,
the body of Christ.  I've listened today.  I've heard about so
many church-based organizations, but I haven't heard much about
the church itself.  My passion is the church.  I look at the 350,000
religious congregations in this country -- with an average membership
of roughly 100 people per congregation -- and I think of what
those 35 million Christians could accomplish.  The potential is
awesome.  We have five times more churches than post offices and
35 times more churches than McDonald's restaurants.

<p>

The church is clearly the most sustainable local organization,
yet I hear so little about the role the church and its members
can play in this process of reaching, reconciling and healing
lives.  The experience of an organization I founded called Love,
Inc. says very clearly that there are Christians in every community
who are prepared to help, to give hope, to share love if 
they are approached -- if they have the appropriate training --
and if they are affirmed for that relationship.  What I learned
with Love, Inc., through the 300,000 volunteers, was that we don't
need heroes.  We need very simple, very basic people.  People
like me and like many of you who are prepared to come alongside
someone who needs principally love, nurture, and affirmation.

<p>

I was challenged two years ago by an organization called International
Aid to put my passions to work.  They said, &quot;Virg, can you
create a model that will somehow engage church members themselves
in the lives of the most at-risk children and families?&quot;
I spent a year researching that.  Instead of promoting answers,
I asked questions.  I went to people who were involved with health
services and human services, education, religion, government services,
and professional volunteer services.  I asked them three questions,
and the answers to those questions forever transformed my approach
to ministry.

<p>

<center><h3>THREE QUESTIONS TO THE HELPING COMMUNITY:</h3></center>

<p>

The first question was: <i>&quot;What are the needs faced by
our children and families?&quot;</i>

<p>

We all read these things in the newspaper, but I wanted to know
how the experts would define the need.  What I heard absolutely
broke my heart.  If you can look into some of the faces of these
children experiencing the pain and despair that is a part of their
lives and <I>not</I> cry, you have a problem.  I came to the conclusion
that America either does not care for its children or does not
know how to care.  How else can you explain the fact that more
children in this country will be pregnant, murdered, drug-dependent,
incarcerated, or poor than the children of any other industrialized
country?  How else can you explain the fact that 0-3-year-old
children are now some of the most neglected children in the entire
world?  One out of every four of our children lives in poverty.
Thirty-one percent live in fatherless homes.  The litany of woe
goes on and on.

<p>

Then I wanted to find out, <i>&quot;Why so much need?&quot;</i>

<p>

I went into my own community and discovered to my dismay that
in Holland, Michigan, an idyllic place along the Lake Michigan
shoreline, with literally a church on every corner and an unemployment
rate of  3 percent, we have had a youth violence increase of 400
percent over the last five years.  Four hundred percent!  That
exceeds the national average by 300 percent.  &quot;Why?&quot;
I asked.  &quot;Why are so many of these young people engaging
in personally and socially destructive behaviors?&quot;  Every
expert said to me, &quot;It's because these young people and children
are desperate for affirmation and for value. Someone needs to
say to them, 'You have value.  You have purpose.  You have meaning
in this community.  Your life has meaning.'&quot;

<p>

Children are looking in all the wrong places for affirmation.
Affirmation is the key need for all of us, and we will find it
-- if not in appropriate ways, then we will find it in <I>in</I>appropriate
ways.  More and more young people are turning toward gangs, for
example.  Michigan has 83 counties, and we have organized gang
activity now in 44 of the 83 counties.

<p>

A 15-year-old boy in my community joined one of four major gangs,
two of which came out of Los Angeles.  The ceremony was as brief
as it was brutal.  They said to him, &quot;Armando, all you have
to do is stand here and take our beating for two minutes without
resisting.&quot;  All the men wore steel-toed boots.  For two
minutes they brutalized this kid.  Absolutely brutalized him.
At the end of two minutes, he was required to stand up, embrace
each man, and call him brother.  Then he was allowed as a reward
to participate in front of all the men in sex with a girl who
had also become part of the gang.  The initiation ceremony for
girls, as some of you know, is much, much worse.

<p>

The next day someone went to him and said, &quot;Armando, why?
Why would you allow yourself to go through that?&quot;  His answer
was immediate.  He said, &quot;I knew this was going to hurt really
bad, but I felt that if I could take it for just a couple of minutes,
I'd be surrounded by people who loved me.&quot;  That's the name
of the game, friends.

<p>

My second-grade daughter (two years ago) was asked to join a gang
by a little girl whose principal characteristic was her body odor.
She would crawl under the teacher's desk periodically and moan,
&quot;No one loves me.  No one loves me.  No one loves me.&quot;
Children would not stand in line with her.  They would point
at her and laugh.  Finally, she also began to move toward gang
activity.  Second grade!  She wanted my daughter to go along with
her.  But my daughter did a revolutionary thing.  Instead of reporting
her to the teacher, she began to pray for her and said to me,
&quot;Daddy, I'm going to be her friend.&quot;  My daughter became
her friend.

<p>

Other teenagers, young people, are turning to pregnancy.  Talk
to anyone working with pregnant girls.  Ask them why these girls
are pregnant.  Sex has nothing to do with it.  These girls in
most cases are so desperate for someone to love and value them,
for someone to hold them, for someone to be intimate for 20 minutes,
that they will endure anything, including pregnancy.  It's a desperate
situation out there.

<p>

Others who do not find affirmation turn to suicide.  Our suicide
rate for young people is up three times -- a three-time increase
in 10 years.  One of the second-graders we had hoped to place
in a loving relationship through Kids Hope is no longer eligible
for our program.  He tried to kill himself and was institutionalized.
I was horrified.  I went to the school and I said, &quot;You're
going to have to help me understand this.  I have a second-grade
daughter.  How does a second-grader arrive at trying to kill himself?&quot;
The teacher said, very simply, &quot;These children, whose lives
are so desperate and without hope, conclude that death is safer
than life.  So they choose death.&quot;  It's happening more and
more.

<p>

Experts told me that we can expect to lose a generation of children.
This will be the first time we have lost a generation in this
country without a war.

<p>

My next question for them was: <i>&quot;What should the church
do?  Do you see a role for the church?&quot;</i>

<p>

Almost to a person they gave me the same answer.  &quot;Virg,&quot;
they said, &quot;it's really not very complex.  Tell the church
to mobilize its members to form one-to-one relationships with
the youngest children.  Tell them to go in to the elementary schools
and work with children who are at that critical age when values
are formed, self-esteem is developed, and critical academic and
problem-solving skills must be acquired.  Virg, tell them to do
that.&quot;

<p>

The mayor of my city when asked what we should do about the violence
in our city said, &quot;We don't need any more programs.&quot;
Michigan, as you may know, has 40,000 non-profit organizations,
not counting churches.  We don't need any more programs.  We need
more caring adults to put an arm around a troubled child and say,
&quot;I love you.  I love you, Judy, Tom, Mary, Sammy, Armando.
I love you.&quot;

<p>

Ron Vogel, former national director of the WIC program, met with
me once to talk about church involvement.  I said, &quot;What
do you think, Ron?  Can a church play a role in meeting the needs
of the WIC mothers and their children?&quot;  He said, &quot;Tell
you what.  I can give the churches a strategy that they can use
to single-handedly reduce the incidence of infant mortality, low
birth weight and long-term dependence on the public health system.&quot;
I said, &quot;Ron, let's do it.  How much will it cost?&quot;
And he said, &quot;Nothing.  All I want the church to do is to
mobilize its mothers and its grandmothers to form one-to-one relationships
with pregnant young women.  Talk to the young women about breast-feeding
and get them to the clinic on time.  If they do only that, they
will transform a generation of young, black women.&quot;

<p>

Anacostia, in southeast Washington, at that point had the highest
infant mortality rate in the country.  At precisely the same time
I heard that statistic, an African-American young woman who worked
in a local ministry came to me and said, &quot;We don't know what
to do.  We have African-American grandmothers who are complaining
to their pastors and others that they no longer have any value
in their church or their community.&quot;  This is all about people.
We have to reestablish the people issue.  It's not about welfare
reform.  That can be a very nice intellectual dodge, but the reality
is that we're talking about people with resources and people in
pain.

<p>

Sometimes people who are very cynical say to me, &quot;Virg, do
you really think that God is in our world?&quot;  I say, &quot;Absolutely.
I can take you right to where He is.&quot;  They say, &quot;Well,
where would I go?&quot;  And I say, &quot;At the intersection
of a caring Christian and a child or any other person in need.
That's where my God lives.&quot;  He's out there right now. 
People in urban ministry encounter God countless times every day
and every month and every year.  That's the potential.

<p>

I recently asked someone who works with troubled children in my
area what kind of children he wants Kids Hope to love.  I expected
a wonderfully learned and long-winded answer.  He surprised me.
He said, &quot;Virg, focus on the children who need hugs.&quot;
I've been thinking about that now for about six months.  I like
what that says about the potential of the body of Christ.  What
if the local body of Christ were known as that distinctive organization
within the community that formed relationships with kids and families
and hugged them?

<p>

<center><h3>FOLLOW-UP QUESTIONS TO THE CHURCH:</h3></center>

<p>

I asked the experts one last question: <i>&quot;Will the church
do that?&quot;</i>

<p>

Without any hesitation, almost everyone said the same thing: 
&quot;No way.  We know we can count on the church for commodities,
for holiday food baskets, for food pantries, for clothing closets,
for a ride to the doctor, for Vacation Bible School, and for all
that is wonderful and necessary in many cases.  We have found
to our dismay, however, that we cannot rely upon the church for
relationships.  We've had to turn elsewhere for relationships.&quot;

<p>

I didn't want to believe that because I have worked with church
volunteer programs for 20 years.  I went out and began to survey
pastors -- determined to prove these people wrong because I believe
that relationships are at the heart of our Gospel.  Without relationships,
there is no reconciliation.  I'm not sure there is redemption.
So I surveyed pastors from churches ranging in size from 50 members
to 6,000 members.

<p>

I asked one question:  <I>&quot;How many of your members are engaged
in one-to-one relationships with at-risk elementary school children
in the neighborhood of your church?&quot;</I>  Out of a combined
membership of 30,000, I found fewer than 20.

<p>

My follow-up question was: <i>&quot;How many of your families
are in relationships with some of the families of the children?&quot;</i>
The answer was fewer than 10.

<p>

That doesn't make sense to me.  Seventy-nine percent of all church
growth is attributed to a person, a friend or a relative, telling
someone about Jesus Christ.  We're investing all kinds of money
in programs and agencies.  Only 10 percent of Americans now have
any sort of significant relationship with a non-believer.  Eighty
percent of all people who accept Jesus Christ do so by age 18,
yet every church I visited was dedicating the vast majority of
its outreach and evangelism money to programs touching people
20 years old and older.  It's a wonderful strategy to fail, and
sadly, it's not reaching these hurting children and their families.

<p>

Do Christians care?  Absolutely.  I get letters and phone calls
virtually every day and have for 20 years.  When we were establishing
Love, Inc., I had calls from every state.  Then we began to get
calls and letters from other countries.  Every request sounded
the same.  People said,  &quot;We want to share the love of Christ
with the poor and we don't know how to do it and our church doesn't
know how to help us.  Can you get something started here?&quot;
There are so many people who care.

<p>

Recently, I went into a large church and I said to them, &quot;Your
church is going into the neighborhood school in eight months to
work with at-risk elementary school children.  Next Sunday, I'm
going to walk from this church to that school.  I invite you to
go with me one mile.&quot;  I had a feeling that my wife, my two
daughters and I would have a very leisurely stroll.  God surprised
me.  I showed up at the church the next Sunday, and 250 men, women
and children were standing there.

<p>

We walked a mile to the school, and then we held hands as we circled
the school.  Forget church-state.  We simply held hands.  We prayed
for those children.  We prayed asking God to bless our commitment
to transform and love those children.

<p>

I still have people coming up to me saying, &quot;Virg, what we
needed was a symbol.&quot;  Bob Woodson has said very appropriately
that conservatives, Christians and Republicans -- not necessarily
in that order -- are much less adept than liberals and Democrats
at using symbols.  I'm finding that so many people want to rally
around this vision of helping and loving a child -- especially
when given a symbol.

<p>

The key problem I found in churches is not a lack of compassion.
As I inquired into the organizational structure, every church
I worked with had the same problem.  They lacked any sort of system
or infrastructure for the recruitment, training, supervision and
affirmation of volunteers. It's like a small business trying to
operate without a personnel department.  Most of these churches
could characterize their ministry by saying, &quot;We pay, we
pray, and we give stuff away.  We do wonderful, wonderful things,
but we never change any lives or any situations.&quot;

<p>

Our call at Kids Hope is to go into one church at a time and to
create that infrastructure within each individual church so that
they can engage their members in the lives of other children.
My past work has all been devoted to community agencies.  I would
go into communities and set up agencies to draw together the resources
of hundreds of churches.  I've changed.  I found that, when many
churches are involved in a project, every church owns it and no
church owns it.  The director of the church-based organization
will spend 70 percent of his or her time raising money, 10 percent
managing public relations, and the rest just feeling generally
frustrated.

<p>

The church is the one most sustainable local organization.  If
we can give them an infrastructure, a personnel department designed
to link their members with children and families in the neighborhood,
we can change the lives of the church members and the lives of
those people needing help.  The church simply giving out food,
money or clothing is not going to make it.  That's the same kind
of commodity distribution that the welfare system has tried for
so long, and it has not worked.

<p>

We are the body of Christ.  We have the most awesome potential,
not just to share Christ but to share that transforming, reconciling
message that can change and empower lives.  That's what we can
do.  If we have 35 million Christians in this country, I contend
that we need to apply the Gideon principle to them.  Remember
when Gideon fought the Midianites?  He started with a ridiculously
small army of 32,000.  God stripped His army until He was left
with less than 1 percent.

<p>

If we look at 1 percent of the existing church membership, we're
looking at 350,000 people.  If each of those people gives a dollar
a week for a year, that will amount to $18,200,000.  If each volunteers
an hour a week, valued at $10 per hour, that labor will be worth
$182,000,000.  That remnant alone can contribute $200,200,000
to transforming outreach.  We must not demean the potential of
the body of Christ -- the very means, the arms and the legs that
He has given us to reach out.

<p>

Let me conclude by sharing the metaphor that has really guided
my ministry.  Because I'm about children and the church, this
really struck me.  A number of years ago, during the Vietnam conflict,
a number of Vietnam veterans were shipped to a hospital in San
Diego.  What they shared in common was that they had lost all
of their arms and legs.  They were lying with simply their heads
and torsos on beds.  They had fallen into such a profound depression
that they simply could not speak.  They were hiding within themselves.
The registered nurse on the floor tried everything to get them
out of their depression, but she failed.

<p>

Finally, in creative frustration, she called the other nurses
together and said, &quot;Gather up all of the terminally-ill babies
in the hospital and strap them face down to the torsos of these
veterans.&quot;  As she left the room, she said to the veterans,
&quot;Gentlemen, these babies are dying.  Most have no visits.
No one to love them.  There is no one to bond with them, and
you have nothing to do.  Your job is to love these babies.&quot;

<p>

The nurses left the room.  They did this day after day.  And in
less than one week, all of the Vietnam veterans had escaped their
depression and were orchestrating the care of the babies.  Each
man fought it, but every time he opened his eyes the eyes of a
little baby were penetrating his soul, looking for that heart
of compassion that had to be in there.

<p>

Those terminally-ill babies, I think, are the children and the
families in our society.  We're losing them.  We are losing a
generation of children.  The veterans, I believe, are the body
of Christ, if it refuses to minister in the name of Christ.  If
it refuses to be the arms and legs of the church, the church and
Christ Himself will be powerless.

<p>

But the church could also be the nurses.  God calls us to be that
creative force, calling the culture -- not just to an awareness
of the need -- but to a realization of what the Christian community
can do in responding to that need.  Our task is, not simply to
hold that baby up in the maternity ward to show people how cute
it is, but rather to hold the baby up and to suggest specific
strategies that the church, the body of Christ, can use in reaching
out to children.  We must love them, touch them, put an arm around
those babies as they grow older and say, &quot;I love you.  Jesus
Christ loves you, and that will make all the difference in your
world and mine.&quot;

<p>

One of our dear volunteers has shown the humor of God.  This woman
is one of the wealthiest women I have ever met.  She works with
Kids Hope through her church.  She has been assigned to a child
from one of the poorest families in her county.  She noticed that
Billy needed shoes, badly.  The teacher said, &quot;Don't buy
them.  It will cause a major disruption in the family.&quot;

<p>

The volunteer came to me and said, &quot;Virg, it's killing me.
I need to buy Billy a pair of shoes, but they won't let me.&quot;
This woman could buy Billy a shoe store if she wanted to.

<p>

I said to her, &quot;What did the teacher ask you to do?  Did
she ask you to buy shoes?&quot;  She answered, &quot;No.  She
said, 'Minnie, could you love this boy?  Could you help this boy
understand how important he is?'  So that's what I've been doing.&quot;

<p>

I talked to Minnie the next week and I said, &quot;How's that
coming, that love business?&quot;  She said, &quot;It's incredible.
I came into school last week and Billy was on the other side
of the school, at the other end of the hallway, and he saw me.
He opened his arms and he began to run down the hallway shouting
at the top of his lungs, 'Mrs. Matthews!  Mrs. Matthews!  Mrs.
Matthews!'  Then he came next to me and scooped me up in a hug.&quot;

<p>

This is a first-grade boy.  He didn't need shoes nearly as badly
as he needed love.  The church has always been there to give Billy
shoes.  The Billy's in our world now need above all else to be
loved and valued.

<p>

No agency -- public, private or para-church -- can do that because
their role is to respond to need.  The role of the church is to
respond to people.  We can do it.  We have the answer to this
problem.  We can create an army to attack these child and family
problems, but we need the people and they need the vision of a
healing and loving God.  Thank you.

<p>
-- 12/13/95
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Dr. Virgil Gulker is the founder and president of Kids Hope
USA, a new volunteer service model that places person-to-person
involvement at the heart of a community's support for children
and families.  He is also the founder of Love, Inc., a network
that has engaged over 300,000 church members around the world
in service to their communities.  Dr. Gulker is the author of
several books including </I>Help Is Just Around the Corner<I>
and </I>Helping You Is Helping Me. <I>To contact Kids Hope USA,
please call (616) 846-7490.  For more information about Love,
Inc., please call (616) 895-5683.</i>

<p>

