<html>
<title>Homeschoolers: Pioneers of Freedom</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/podium/podium.gif">
<h2>HOMESCHOOLERS:<br>
PIONEERS OF FREEDOM</h2>
<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Robert G. Morrison</i></center>
<p>
We have in our office &quot;Goals 1996.&quot;  We're moving a little bit
more quickly than Goals 2000.  Our goals for 1996 include the
dis-establishment of the U.S. Department of Education, to undo
what President Carter did back in 1979.  He created the department
to meet a commitment that he made to the National Education Association.
 We opposed the creation of a Department of Education in 1979,
and we've seen nothing in the last 16 years to justify its continued
existence. Our sincere belief is that the appropriate federal
role in education is no federal role in education.  Our Constitution
does not call upon our federal government to be running schools
from Washington, D.C.  We will very energetically support other
leaders in Washington trying to dis-establish the U.S. Department
of Education.  The key point is that $70 billion of our money
goes into Washington, D.C. to be spent on education, money we
think can be better spent by states and communities and localities
and, most importantly, by parents and taxpayers themselves.  Our
emphasis is going to be on local schools and local leaders.
<p>
We're also going to call for the repeal of Goals 2000 legislation which
was passed last year.  Now, Goals 2000 is one of the most important
education bills ever in this respect:  it is, in effect, the nationalization
of American public education, bringing more power and authority
into Washington, D.C.  It's very interesting that this happened
because, at the same time, the United States considered a health
care plan which was devised by Ira Magaziner and Mrs. Clinton,
a health care plan which would have centralized authority and
power and eliminated choices.  The American people and their Congress
rightly considered and, we believe, rightly rejected that idea.
  But that's because there was a serious national debate, and
we actually looked into the plan and carefully analyzed it.  Americans
understood what they were being offered and said, &quot;No, we
don't want it.&quot;
<p>
Unfortunately, we did not get the same quality
of debate and discussion about Goals 2000 that we did about the
Clinton health care plan.  Interestingly, Ira Magaziner and Hillary
Clinton played a part in devising the Goals 2000 plan over the
last half decade or more as well.  But we're not here to represent
one political party or another, and we have to be fair because
President Bush actually introduced America 2000 back in 1991.
 His Secretary of Education, Lamar Alexander, supported America
2000.  Now we think Goals 2000 is even worse than America 2000.
 But the principle had given way, and too much control was already
coming to Washington in America 2000.
<p>
It made it very difficult to leverage opposition to Goals 2000 in Washington
when a lot of the Republican members on Capitol Hill said, &quot;How
can we vote against Goals 2000?  Didn't we endorse pretty much
the same thing just a year or so ago?&quot;
<p>
We said, &quot;Yes, regrettably you did, and we were trying to talk to you about 
that, but we didn't get anyone's attention.&quot;
<p>
So now we are working on the repeal of Goals 2000.  Let me draw from my Coast 
Guard days to create a metaphor.  If you look at the Elementary and
Secondary Education Act, it's a huge liner. It's an $11.6 billion
piece of legislation, another bill to extend power and authority
over our communities.  Most states cannot say no to their share
of $11.6 billion.  If you look at Goals 2000, it doesn't look
that big.  It's only $700 million.  I realize I'm working in Washington
where you talk about a billion here, a billion there -- pretty
soon you're talking about money.   But if you think of Goals 2000
as a small tugboat guiding and pushing that huge liner, you'll
get an idea as to why Goals 2000 is so vital.  It's not that big
money is involved, but it's the power and direction that the program
gives.
<p>
One of the reasons I especially wanted to come speak to
you is to express our deep gratitude and appreciation to you as
homeschoolers for what you have done to help transform the picture
in Washington.  I'm talking about what happened last year with
H.R. 6, the Elementary and Secondary Education Act, that was going
through the House of Representatives.  When you were threatened
with something called the Miller Amendment, which had the potential
almost to outlaw private education, religious schools and homeschools
in the effect that it would have had down the line, you created
a sensation in Washington, D.C.  A sensation, I should mention,
that has never really been noticed by the Washington Post, the
New York Times, Dan Rather or Connie Chung.  Maybe we'll just
try to get Gary to whisper it to Connie Chung....
<p>
It was a major event to be there at ground zero, with hundreds of thousands
of phone calls coming in from all over America about H.R. 6. 
Not every member of Congress had been following H.R. 6 with rapt
attention.  Many of them were interested in the agriculture bill,
the trade bill, or NAFTA, or military issues or foreign trade
-- all these other things -- and they weren't too concerned about
what was going on in a committee about education.  But all of
a sudden their phones lit up.  They couldn't make any phone calls
in or out, their faxes were completely tied up, and they were
finally saying, &quot;What are they talking about?  Who are they?&quot;
 Well, there's a sign chiseled in the House of Representatives,
right over one of the passages, that says, &quot;Here, sir, the
people rule.&quot;  They are the people, sir.   That's who's calling
you.  That's where you're getting your phone calls from.  We recognize
and honor the role of leaders, leaders like Carol Lee Adams, the
homeschooling mother in New Jersey who actually brought this whole
thing to our attention.  She immediately contacted Michael Farris,
us, and a committee staff on Capitol Hill.  We certainly honor
leaders like Dr. Dobson and Gary Bauer, but none of this could
have happened if you just had a group of leaders calling each
other and expressing their indignation.  None of this earthquake
could have occurred unless there was this coast-to-coast, popular
uprising against this very dangerous bill.  So that's why I wanted
to come and thank the earthquake for what happened there.
<p>
What happened on Capitol Hill reminds me of the parable in the Gospel
of Luke of the widow and the unjust judge.  &quot;And for a while,
[the judge] was unwilling.  But afterward he said to himself,
even though I do not fear God nor respect man, yet because this
widow bothers me, I will give her legal protection, lest by her
continually coming she wear me out.&quot;   I like that, but,
of course, in Washington, not everyone likes you to cite Scripture.
 So I would recommend to those believers in the gospel of Charles
Darwin that you ought to at least recognize that you don't come
between a she-bear and her cubs.  That is a very dangerous thing
to do.
<p>
The lesson to draw from this blitz over H.R. 6 is the
need for accurate and timely communication.  We are moving very
quickly with fax networks, telephone trees, with newsletters,
with radio broadcasts, and even on the Internet.  We have the
ability to communicate with one another quickly and accurately
to check information.  That is a major step forward that is going
to be used by the pro-family movement generally, and especially
by homeschoolers.  I think it also proves to us that, in our time,
decentralization of power is a reality.  We do not believe that
Washington, D.C. has all the answers to all the problems in our
lives.  And decentralization of information is making possible
a revitalization of local democracy.  So decentralization works.
<p>
I think it also proves to us that Americans are capable.  For
a long time now we have proceeded on the idea that Americans don't
know how to run their own affairs.  With all of these legislative
measures that have come through, be it the health care plan, be
it the education plan, even in many ways in the crime bill, it
was assumed that we had to go to Washington with our hats in hands
saying, &quot;Please, our rulers, will you govern us?  Will you
somehow free us from our local problems?&quot;  The  H.R. 6 battle
proved that Americans are capable.
<p>
The homeschooling movement is much more than this remarkable episode over H.R. 6. 
I honor the commitment that homeschoolers make, and I have found some
things about the movement that I think are important to all Americans.
<p>
I know one of the first questions that you are all asked is,
&quot;How will your children be socialized if they are homsechooled?&quot;
 That has been one of the major concerns of American public education.
 I have always thought that you may fail there -- you may not
actually meet the national standards in <i>socialization</i> of kids
-- but your children will instead be <i>civilized</i> and that wouldn't
be bad at all.
<p>
You have also taught a lesson in democracy to
the entire country.  We have two drop-out problems in our country.
  One is the school drop-out rate.  But I'd say there's another
drop-out problem that gets less attention, and that's the drop-out
of citizens.  In this great free republic of ours in 1994, only
39% of eligible Americans voted in the Congressional elections.
 These were perhaps the most important Congressional elections
in a generation, yet only 39% voted.  That, by the way, was a
very good turn-out for an off-year election, the best in over
20 years.  But nonetheless, it suggested six out of 10 Americans
did not even exercise the right to vote which was bought with
blood for them.  That's not America the way it ought to be.  
We need to have more citizens engaged.  Homeschoolers are teaching
a lesson in citizen involvement that I think is very important,
and that is gaining respect, even from some people who are not
otherwise sympathetic.  William Raspberry, a leading columnist
in Washington, D.C., is generally liberal and many times writes
columns that I do not agree with.  But William Raspberry has been
kindly disposed toward homeschoolers.
<p>
Homeschoolers are doing something for all of us as American citizens, whether 
we homeschool our children or not.  A hundred years ago, Frederick Jackson Turner,
a great American historian, spoke about the closing of the American
frontier.  He cited it as a significant event in American history
because the frontier had affected the entire development of our
country and our institutions.  The famous Turner thesis was that,
if you were living on the Eastern Seaboard or in the Midwest,
and if your  employer, if your community, even if your family
or church, if any of the structured institutions in your life
became oppressive to you, if they crushed your spirit, you always
had the option of going out to territories and starting a new
life.  This westward movement was a constant in American life.
<p>
Though we no longer have that kind of frontier, homeschoolers
are pioneers in a very real sense, creating a new option, a new
frontier in education that benefits every American citizen.  By
sometimes wrestling, sometimes litigating, sometimes battling
with the state authorities, homeschoolers bring the state into
a right relationship with the citizens.  It's no longer master
and servant, senior and subject, but basically citizen and government.
 When a state government recognizes the right of parents to educate
their own children -- and note I say recognize but not grant,
because it is a <i>recognition</i> that we seek -- when the state recognizes
that right, it comes into a proper relationship and all of us
benefit.  We are all strengthened by what homeschoolers are doing.
<p>
Homeschoolers are also restoring some of the academic seriousness
in education through a commitment to educational excellence. 
So much of what we've seen in education is tragic.  In the teaching
of reading there has been an obvious &quot;dumbing down&quot;
of Americans.  The Department of Education itself admitted in
October of 1993 in a national adult literacy survey that 46% of
Americans could read at a level beyond the rudimentary level --
less than half of American adults could read anything beyond a
rudimentary level.  Now we have to have historical memory and
compare that with our own past.  James McPherson, a Civil War
historian, tells us that 90% of Union soldiers in the Civil War
were literate.  80% of Confederate soldiers in the Civil War were
literate.  Compare that with 46% today.  I would challenge any
of the opponents of homeschooling to see homeschooled children
anywhere in the United States who are not getting that vital basic
skill of reading.
<p>
I believe we must recognize what so often is
not recognized in our public education establishment:  the vital
importance of the Bible as a way to transmit literacy.  E.D. Hirsch,
a professor at the University of Virginia and neither a Christian
nor a conservative, has written a book on cultural literacy in
which he points to the Bible as the basis for English language
literacy.  He cited a fascinating example about India, where there
are over 400 languages.  In order to have a unified country, to
conduct debates in the Indian parliament or to conduct business
or commerce, Indians must speak English.  It's the only common
language they have, and the people of India must be familiar with
the Bible so they can understand the wealth of images and sayings
of the English language.  How else to understand the cultural
concepts of &quot;go the extra mile,&quot; the widow and the unjust
judge, David and Goliath and a host of other references that come
from Scripture.  Yet, our public education establishment has been
militantly opposed to imparting a greater knowledge of the Bible
to our young people.
<p>
Homeschoolers promote the importance of fiscal
responsibility.  Many of you are making a tremendous sacrifice
to educate your children, but you do so efficiently and wisely.
 In contrast, it costs the United States taxpayers in our country
some $5,500 per child to achieve not very great results in education.
 That is a national tragedy.  And all we ever hear is that they
need more, they need more.  Several years ago I met a very fine
public school principal down in Alabama who agreed with us on
so many things, yet he said, &quot;You people are always arguing
for less money for education.  We need more. And the reason that
we need more is that we don't have enough toilet paper in our
high school.  And that just is an example of how awful things
are.&quot;  Well, this roll I hold in my hand I got from a homeschool
-- I can tell you there's plenty wherever private enterprise reigns.
 The one place I know where there was a lack of such things was
on Soviet ships when they had to call Moscow and say, &quot;Hey,
we need basic commodities.&quot;  Albert Shanker, the head of
the American Federation of Teachers, has compared American public
education to Soviet agriculture, and I have an idea of what he
means.
<p>
The final thing I will say is that we've seen the involvement
of parents, of husbands and wives, coming closer together with
their children, and that has been characteristic of the homeschool
movement.  As I sat there in Washington during the H.R. 6 battle
and got hundreds of phone calls, 90% percent of them were from
mothers who were deeply concerned for the welfare of their children.
 I thought what a remarkable thing it was, and that people in
the secular political world who do studies and  write columns
ought to pay attention to this, because what you are seeing is
not a woman's movement, but a mother's movement.  You are seeing
a new movement, a new thing happening in American society.  The
feminist movement, theoretically put, argued for barriers between
mother and child in their advocacy of abortion on demand, barriers
and conflict between husbands and wives, barriers even between
women and their God.  In the homeschooling movement we have seen
all of those conflicts be resolved and all of those barriers come
down.  That's why I find homeschooling so exciting, and why I
will invite the interest of many of our friends in the press and
the academic community to study it and see this new thing happening
in America.  That's why I've come from Washington to thank you.
God bless you all.
<p>
-- 9/21/95
<p><center>***</center><p>
<i>Robert G. Morrison, an Education Policy Analyst at the Family Research 
Council, a Washington, DC-based research and advocacy organization, delivered 
this address on April 6, 1995 to the River Cities Christian Home Educators 
Conference in Huntington, West Virginia.</i>

<p>

